<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Clashes Occurred in Umm Al-Fahem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Local Arab residents of Umm
Al-Fahem clashed with Israeli police on Monday, causing more
injuries, Israeli Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The local Arab residents went to the streets to protest
against the Sunday's police crackdown on protesters and against
the confiscation of their land by the army.
</P>
<P>
The protesters blocked several main roads leading to Umm
Al-Fahem and the police fired tear gas to disperse them.
</P>
<P>
During the clashes, more people were injured and the police
also arrested some residents.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Al-Tibi, Advisor to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
went Monday to Umm Al-Fahem along with several Israeli Arab
leaders to try to help the local residents to reach a compromise
with the authorities on the land issue, but failed.
</P>
<P>
Tibi was also injured during the clash, the Radio said.
</P>
<P>
All Israeli Arab villagers around Umm Al-Fahem joined a
general strike on Monday to protest against Sunday's police's
crackdown on protesters.
</P>
<P>
The strike was called Sunday night by the Israeli Arab
Leadership Monitoring Committee following violent clashes between
Israeli police and local Arab residents in which over 90 people
were injured.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army said that the disputed area, near the northern
edge of the West Bank, is an army's firing range. The army
also said that an agreement was reached with the residents to
nationalize about 50 hectares of land in exchange for about
six times as much land elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
