<HEADLINE> Britain's Chancellor Favors Joining Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLACKPOOL, Britain, September 28 (Xinhua) -- British finance
minister Gordon Brown said here on Monday that Britain will not
rule out joining the single currency as its economic interests
lied in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Labor Party Conference at this northwestern
coastal city, the Chancellor of the Exchequer said that at a time
when the balance of risks in the world economy is shifting, "a
Britain facing up to the challenges must work with other countries
and implement a reform agenda for global stability and growth."
</P>
<P>
"A Britain which sees that our national economic interest lies
in a Europe, that is a zone of stability and growth will reject
the isolationism of the Conservative Party, and refuse to rule out
constructive engagement, particularly on the single currency, on
the basis of ideological dogma."
</P>
<P>
So far Britain has stated it would not join the first wave of
the single currency in the current parliament that ends in 2001
under strong domestic pressure. The European Monetary Union will
be launched on January 1, 1999 and 11 out of 15 EU members have
qualified to join the single currency at the first wave.
</P>
<P>
He said the task of the British government was to make the
country equipped for every challenge of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Brown also said that to ensure global coordination and a better
equipped IMF and World Bank, the British government will put
forward a proposal at next weeks IMF meeting in Washington on a
new and pioneering global code of conduct for social policy.
</P>
<P>
He would travel to the IMF on Tuesday personally to argue for
policies for stability, growth and fairness to ensure that our
obligations to the unemployed and the vulnerable are nmet in every
part of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
