<HEADLINE> Clinton, Arafat, Netanyahu Meet over Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat on Monday began a meeting to break an
impasse in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met
Netanyahu and Arafat in New York preparing for the summit.
</P>
<P>
Both Netanyahu and Arafat ignored reporters' questions as they
arrived at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which will last about one hour, was expected to
yield progress in tortuous negotiations involving further Israeli
troop withdrawals from the West Bank in return for detailed
Palestinian security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli source told Xinhua that the three leaders might
issue a statement later in the day. An agreement between Israel
and Palestine could be reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
