<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore FM Calls for Sticking to Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Foreign Minister
S. Jayakumar, has outspoken to defend globalization, as Asia's
economic crisis is arousing more skepticism over the drive,
according to a summary released by his ministry.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the 53rd session of the United Nations
General Assembly Monday, Jayakumar said the way ahead is not to
turn backs on globalization, adding that it is not a viable or
realistic option.
</P>
<P>
"To repudiate globalization will hurt our long-term growth
prospects," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing there was "no subject more important" than
globalization, Jayakumar said: "The process of globalization had
enhanced the free flow of goods and services, capital and
information, spurred innovation and competition and lifted
hundreds of millions of people out of poverty."
</P>
<P>
While emphasizing that East Asia had enjoyed unprecedented
growth, he conceded that the opening up to the global market by
the economies desiring for a freer flow of capital had made them
more vulnerable, and the forces of globalization had transformed
what should have been a national problem into a regional problem
that was fast threatening to become a global crisis.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar cautioned against the temptation to take the easiest
way and close doors on globalization. Instead, he called for the
U.N. to play a leading role in the international effort to help
countries "reap the benefit of globalization."
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the alternative -- to turn the clock back
and walk away from free trade -- would have implications that were
not just domestic or merely economic.
</P>
<P>
"If countries were unable to gain access to the raw materials,
goods and services they need through peaceful and open
competition, they would resort to other means," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Economic rivalries could have political and military
consequences and a return to global tensions could not be ruled
out," he added.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that the only way forward was to find solutions to
deal with the vulnerabilities brought by globalization, and called
for higher standards of government, the strengthening of
regulatory and supervisory frameworks, the improvement of
corporate governance, increased transparency, and less government
interference in market decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
