<HEADLINE> Germany's SPD to Begin Coalition Talks with Greens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Social Democratic
Party (SPD) announced Monday to begin negotiations with the
ecologist Greens on forming a centre-left ruling coalition in Bonn
after a landmark victory in the general election a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
Gerhard Schroeder, who will be Germany's next chancellor after
the election triumph over the veteran chancellor Helmut Kohl, said
at a news conference in Bonn on Monday that the coalition talks
with the Greens will begin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He also described the so-call "Red-Greens Coalition" as the
logical result of Sunday's election, in which Kohl's current
centre-right ruling coalition was voted out of office after 16
years in power.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary official results, a SPD-Greens
coalition would have 21-seat majority in parliament, which
Schroeder said is sufficient to make it possible to form a stable
government.
</P>
<P>
The leadership of the Greens on Monday unanimously approved the
coalition talks with the SPD. It is the first chance for the
Greens to join the government in Bonn after its founding in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU)/Christian
Social Union (CSU) conservative alliance was also engaged in tense
talks to select a new leadership after have seeing their worst
defeat since 1949.
</P>
<P>
Kohl reiterated on Monday that he will not be available for
re-election as the chairman of his CDU at its congress next month,
neither will he seek any post at the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"I'll only stay on as a normal parliament member," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Theo Waigel also announced on Monday that he
will give up the CSU chairmanship to Edmund Stoiber, premier of
the southern German state of Bavaria where the party based.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
