<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Poland Wish Germany to Adhere to Foreign Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma and his Polish counterpart Aleksander Kwasniewski expressed
the hope on Monday that the assumption of German premiership by
Gerhard Shroeder would not lead to fundamental changes in the
country's foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian Interfax News Agency reported that the two
presidents made the remark during their two-day unofficial meeting
in Crimea.
</P>
<P>
The Polish president arrived in Ukraine Sunday night to discuss
with Kuchma how to strengthen the strategic partnership between
the two countries and the impact of the Russian economic crisis on
them.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said, thanks to the efforts by the outgoing German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, the Ukrainian-German bonds had undergone
steady development.
</P>
<P>
He said the new chancellor's platform and political statement
seemed to show that Germany would not change its policies toward
Ukraine. He hoped that the new leader would acknowledge Ukraine's
role and status as much as his predecessor did.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski believed that the Germany's fundamental policies
would persist and that Germany would continue to expand its
cooperation with Poland and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Shroeder, chairman of the German Social-Democratic Party, won
the general election on Sunday and will serve as the new
chancellor of Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
