<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Kicks off Computer Cattle-Tracing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The British government Monday
kicked off a national computer cattle-tracing system in an effort
to boost consumer confidence in British cattle industry.
</P>
<P>
British Agriculture Minister Nick Brown said in a statement
issued early Monday: "This new system will make it easier to
trace cattle if there is a disease outbreak, and give greater
assurance to those buying cattle about an animal's history."
</P>
<P>
"It is also a milestone for consumers, improving confidence in
the food chain," Brown said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The new tracking system, which should help to reassure
consumers after the mad-cow crisis, will track the movements of
every British registered calf, cow and bull from birth until
death.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) imposed a global ban on British beef
exports in March 1996 when the British government admitted
possible links between mad cow disease and its human equivalent
Creutzdelt Jacob Disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. High-Level Delegation Visits Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A high-level
delegation from the United Nations Drug Control Program (UNDCP)
arrived in Iran on Monday on a seven-day visit, U.N. spokesman
Fred Eckhard said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The main purpose of the mission is to elaborate, in close
consultation with the Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran,
a strategy to effectively address the current flow of illicit
opiates into Iran from Afghanistan, and the abuse of these drugs
within the country," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During its stay in Iran, the delegation will appraise the
general drug control situation in Iran and assess the measures
currently being taken by the Iranian Government against the
illicit drug trafficking from Afghanistan, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
They will also review the status and level of activities for
the prevention of drug abuse in Iran, as well as the Government's
efforts to promote public awareness against drug abuse, he said.
</P>
<P>
The current visit is an outcome of the two recent official
visits to Iran by Pino Arlacchi, the executive director of the
Office of Drug Control and Crime Prevention, in April and July
this year. On the both occasions, Arlacchi had an opportunity to
meet with Iranian President Mohmmed Khatemi to discuss matters of
common interest in the field of drug control.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, headed by Vice President of the European
Parliament Renzo Imbeni, is composed of senior diplomats from
Germany and Belgium, high-ranking officials from drug control
organizations in France, Spain and the UNDCP. A law enforcement
consultant from the United Kingdom is also part of the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, Iran has exerted strenuous efforts to stem
the illicit flow of morphine base and heroin of Afghan origin
destined to the illicit markets in the Western countries, by
developing large numbers of law enforcement personnel in the
border areas to combat traffickers and by investing large
financial exclusively from national budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
