<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Woos French Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor arrived in Paris Monday to begin his official visit to
France, with an aim to seek French investment in the west
African country's post-war reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said Taylor will hold talks with French
President Jacques Chirac Monday, and is likely to discuss
possible French assistance in rebuilding the main power plant in
Liberian capital Monrovia, which has not been functioning
properly since the civil war began in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Finance Minister Elie Saleeby, who arrived in Paris
earlier along with other members of the delegation, was quoted as
saying that the talks between the two sides will focus on economic
issues.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also review two important bilateral
agreements on the protection and promotion of investments and
technical cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that seven years of civil war has left a devastated
infrastructure and a substantially displaced population, the
minister said, "Liberia is just emerging from a fragile war
situation and needs international assistance to resolve pressing
post-conflict problems."
</P>
<P>
Critical areas include re-settlement of refugees, re-training,
creation of jobs and rebuilding of the country's social and
economic infrastructure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other members of Taylor's delegation include the ministers of
planning and economic development, of information, culture and
tourism, and of health and social welfare, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
