<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen Opens First Conference on Oil and Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Yemen opened its first
conference on oil and gas here on Monday in an effort to attract
more investment to the economically vital sector.
</P>
<P>
The conference, under the auspices of the Yemeni Ministry of
Oil and Mineral Resources, was to brief investors on Yemen's
economic potentials and its policy on developing oil and gas and
encouraging investment.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Prime Minister Abdul-Karim
al-Iryani said Yemen attaches great importance to new investments
in the oil and gas sector and has signed contracts with five
foreign companies for oil and gas exploration.
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues boosted national economy and brought down the
inflation rate and budget deficit and helped stabilize the
exchange rate of the national currency, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that more investment opportunities will
be created in Yemen's oil and gas sector by the current conference.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Oil and Mineral Resources Mohammad al-Khadim
al-Wajeeh told the participants that his ministry has given
concessions to 13 companies from different countries to prospect
19 out of 57 areas that are hopeful of oil and gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
Five are already producing oil and gas, he said. Another 33
sites are open for investment, and 40 local and foreign firms are
working there, he added.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, attended by some 300 participants
representing Arab and foreign firms and international
organizations, will discuss 60 papers and feasibility studies on
oil and gas exploration in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni government will launch several projects to enhance the
use of gas a source of energy instead of crude oil, whose
production stands at 380,000 barrels a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Pledges Full Cooperation with UN Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraq would cooperate
fully With the U.N. chief in good faith as well as in a
professional and objective manner in solving the recent standoff
between the United Nations and Iraq, Tareq Aziz, Iraq's Deputy
Prime Minister, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tareq made the remark after holding one-hour meeting with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan. Aziz and Annan discussed the recent
standoff between Iraq and the United Nations Special Commission in
charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction (UNSCOM)
as well as Annan's ideas for a comprehensive review of Iraq's
compliance with U.N. resolutions which demand Iraq scrape all its
prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Aziz said " The comprehensive review is
not a reward to Iraq. The Idea that Iraq should do this or that
concession before the comprehensive review takes place is not
legal and is not logical."
</P>
<P>
"The review is a moral and legal action by the U.N. Security
Council itself in accordance with its own resolution 687. That
resolution requires it implement the obligation in every six
days," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq has complied with resolutions of the Security Council for
seven years and a half, and the Security Council has not taken
steps to reduce or lift the sanctions against Iraq according to
its own resolution," Aziz added.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Prime Minister described his meeting with Annan as
cordial and constructive.
</P>
<P>
Aziz arrived at the Headquarters of the United Nations over the
weekend. He will stay here for a couple of days during which he is
due to meet members of the Security Council and to meet the U.N.
chief once again by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The standoff between Iraq and the United Nations came when Iraq
announced to suspend its cooperation with the U.N. weapons
inspectors after talks collapsed between Iraq and UNSCOM in early
August.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Moves to Pay Soldiers' Back Salaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government has
paid off its debt in back wages to soldiers, and students will
soon receive their stipends, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov told
President Boris Yeltsin Monday.
</P>
<P>
Wage and pension arrears have long dogged Russia, where many
workers, teachers and soldiers go without pay for months, even
before the onset of the latest bout of financial crisis that came
to a head August 17 when the Sergei Kiriyenko government
effectively devalued the ruble and defaulted on some domestic and
foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who took office just two weeks ago and is still
struggling to form a fully functioning government, has repeatedly
stressed the payment of such debts as the top priorities.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates published in the Kommersant earlier this
month, Russia owed a total of 2.4 billion U.S. dollars in back
salaries and social payments. Of that sum, 233 million dollars was
owed to the military.
</P>
<P>
The painful process of government-forming continued Monday,
when President Boris Yeltsin appointed Farid Gazizullin as head of
the Committee for State Property Management, the agency in charge
of privatization.
</P>
<P>
Boris Fyodorov, seen in the West as a strong proponent of
market-oriented reform, was dismissed from his posts of acting
deputy prime minister and tax chief. Acting Deputy Prime Minister
Viktor Khristenko was also ousted, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
So far, posts of nine ministers remain vacant, but First Deputy
Prime Minister Vadim Gustov said the formation of the government
had been completed.
</P>
<P>
Gustov made the statement as he presented the new nationalities
minister, Ramazan Abdulatipov, to his subordinates on Monday, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said Yeltsin will appoint Valery Kirpichnikov minister in
charge of regional policy on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kirpichnikov is currently vice-governor of the Leningrad region
and president of the Union of Russian Cities.
</P>
<P>
Judging from Gustov's statement, it appeared that the Primakov
will make do with two first deputy prime ministers and three
deputy prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
The fourth deputy prime minister, Alexander Shokhin, who was
put in charge of financial policy, resigned from the cabinet last
Friday after just 10 days on the job.
</P>
<P>
He said he was stepping down to protest the reappointment of
Mikhail Zadornov as finance minister. He insisted that Shokhin was
among those to blame for the previous cabinet's August 17
decision.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Yeltsin said Shokhin's decision to quit was "an act
not becoming a statesman."
</P>
<P>
Primakov said he was not going to make haste in filling
Shokhin's slot after his "unexpected demarche". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Center for Black Sea Studies Opens in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Center for
Black Sea Studies (ICBS) opened here today with the participation
of representatives of the 11-member Black Sea Economic Cooperation
(BSEC).
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Greece's Deputy Foreign Minister Yiannos
Kranidiotis said that the ICBS would contribute to promoting the
wider goal of the BSEC for greater democracy, peace and
development in the Black Sea region.
</P>
<P>
He also described the BSEC as "a useful tool" to coordinate
between the member states and their desire for stability and
economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
On his part, BSEC Secretary-General Vassil Baytchev said that
the academic communities of the BSEC member states could play a
primary role in cooperation between Governments through the
exchange of information, holding of joint programs, and regional
cooperation in research and technology.
</P>
<P>
The center, an independent body, will aim at finding practical
ways of realizing cooperation between member states in the
technological, academic and economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
The BSEC members are Albania, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Bulgaria,
Georgia, Greece, Moldova, Romania, Russia, Turkey and Ukraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
