<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-28 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Demands Quick Delivery of Oil Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 28 (Xinhua)-- Iraq Monday called for quick
delivery of the badly-needed equipment for its oil sector, blaming
the United States and Britain for the delay of approval of
contracts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh told a press
conference Monday evening that no spare parts for oil equipment
have arrived in Iraq after four months has passed since the start
of the current fourth phase of oil-for-food program which began in
June.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said 28 contracts concerning Iraq's purchase of oil
production equipment had been held by the U.S. and Britain, adding
that a total of 59 contracts valued at more than 200 million
U.S. dollars and concluded under the fourth phase oil-for-food
deal have been blocked by the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister complained that the oil-for-food deal has
not alleviated the suffering of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has complained repeatedly that the slow process of
approving contracts by the U.N. Sanctions Committee on Iraq and
delivering the contracted goods have caused deaths among citizens
suffering curable illnesses and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations agreed to increase the oil-for-food
program to 5.2 billion dollars under the fourth phase from the
previous 2 billion dollars every six months.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. also allowed Iraq to import 300 million dollars worth
of spare parts and equipment to repair its oil facilities.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq says it cannot meet the ceiling but would manage
to sell 4 billion dollars of oil for the current six months period
due to low world oil prices and production problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0032 </DOCNO>
