<HEADLINE> Tajik President, Opposition Leader Discuss Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Tajik President Emomali
Rakhmonov and leader of the country's opposition coalition agreed
Monday to settle all differences through political talks.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmonov and Said Abdullo Nuri, leader of the Unified Tajik
Opposition, signed a 10-point program to stabilize the situation
in the Central Asian republic, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Opposition representatives will resume their work in the
National Reconciliation Commission Tuesday, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
They have been boycotting the commission's meetings since a
killing of a member of the commission, Otakhon Latifi, last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the 10-point program, the security of opposition
representatives working in the National Reconciliation Commission
and the government will be ensured.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a joint commission grouping representatives from
both the government and the opposition will be established to
investigate Latifi's slaying.
</P>
<P>
Opposition representatives will have more portfolios in the
government, occupying up to 30 percent of the seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
