<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Syria Ready for Talks With Turkey Over Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi official has
said that Iraq and Syria are willing to hold dialogs with Turkey
over river water sharing.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Irrigation Minister Abdul Salman voiced the
position after the meeting of a technical committee Monday, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Salman said "Iraq and Syria are ready for dialogs to find a
solution that will take into considerations of the legitimate
rights of these two countries."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Salman said both Iraq and Syria were deeply
concerned over Turkey's continuation in building dams over the
upper reaches of the Tigris and Euphrates, which make it more
difficult for them to get more water.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, Syria and Iraq have long been haggling over the water
sharing of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, which originate in
Turkey and flow down to Syria and Iraq before pouring into the
Persian gulf.
</P>
<P>
Under a protocol signed between Turkey and Syria in 1987,
Turkey releases at least 500 cubic meters of Euphrates water per
second to Syria prior to the completion of Turkey's Ataturk Dam on
the river.
</P>
<P>
The protocol also stipulates that the two countries should
hammer out a new agreement on a higher share once the dam was
completed.
</P>
<P>
The dam was erected in 1991, but no new agreement has been
sealed because of the strained relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of sheltering Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) militants, who have been fighting
since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Iraq have been lobbying the Arab world to pressure
Turkey to release more water to them.
</P>
<P>
But Ankara has insisted that the water dispute should be
discussed only after the Syrian government halt its support to the
PKK.
</P>
<P>
Ankara failed to attend the just concluded six-day meeting of
the tripartite technical committee, which was set up in 1980 and
held its last meeting in 1992, though an invitation was extended.
</P>
<P>
However, Salman said possibilities still exist to continue
these meetings in the future in any time and at any place as long
as Iraq and Syria receive invitation from the Turkish government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
