privately with Netanyahu while Arafat returned to New York to
address the U.N. General Assembly. Arafat is expected to be back
to the White House to meet Clinton on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has been in an impasse because
the Israelis disagreed on a U.S. proposal that Israeli troops
withdraw from 13 percent of the West Bank, claiming it created too
much security risk for Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel agreed reportedly that it would withdraw from 13 percent
of the land if three percent of the territory was set aside as a
nature reserve, where security was provided by Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu met in New York under the auspices of
Albright, the first one-one-one meeting they had in a year.
</P>
