<HEADLINE> 4 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Four rebels of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in recent military
operations launched by Turkish government troops, the Anatolia
News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted an official statement as saying that these
militants, including a woman, died in clashes with government
soldiers in the mountain area of the southeastern province of
Tokat.
</P>
<P>
There was no detail of the clashes or any report of casualties
on government troops.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 14-year-old guerilla war against
the Turkish government for an independent Kurdish state in the
southeastern region.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the PKK, unilaterally declared a
ceasefire late last month, but Ankara rejected the offer, saying
that it would never negotiate with the PKK.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government declared a state of emergency in
southeastern Turkey in 1987. 
</P>
