<HEADLINE> Cyprus, World's Major Ship Management Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has grown into one of
the largest third-party ship management centers in the world,
Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a two-day international meeting on marine insurance
opened here Monday, Christodoulou said there are about 100
offshore enterprises on the island in 1996 with fully fledged
offices which engaged in ship management and other maritime
services.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus ranks fifth on the list of the leading maritime
nations in the world, and the country also enjoys comparative
advantages.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus offers numerous tax incentives and inexpensive
registration and annual fees, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
"However, the Cyprus flag should not be regarded as a flag of
convenience," Christodoulou stressed, noting that Cyprus has
ratified the major international conventions on maritime safety,
prevention of sea pollution, training, certification and
watch-keeping of seafarers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was participated by more than 10 countries from
Europe and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
It will discuss issues relating to insurance of vessels and
cargo transportation, European Union policy on sea safety and
prevention of sea pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
