<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Launch Year of Older Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan will on October 1 launch the International Year of
Older Persons 1999 to promote action strategies on the
fast-changing demographic picture of older persons.
</P>
<P>
Annan will speak on the theme of the year "towards a society
for all ages", the U.N. Department of Public Information said here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Population Division defines older persons as those
aged 60 years and above. Growing longevity has caused global life
expectancy to climb 20 years since 1950 to the current level of 66
years.
</P>
<P>
About 10 percent of the world population is now 60 years or
older. By 2050 the figure will soar to 20 percent and by 2150 it
will be 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
The share of those aged 80 years or older in the older persons'
group will grow from the current 11 percent to 27 percent by 2050.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the numbers and proportions of the aging will
have influence on social and economic development in terms of
health care, employment, social security and other areas
especially in the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The designation of 1999 as the International Year of Older
Persons was decided in 1992 by the U.N. General Assembly to
facilitate older persons' concerns and encourage activities within
a long-term perspective.
</P>
<P>
The Year's activities are expected to focus on raising
awareness of all ages to promote active aging, develop
appropriate care-giving strategies, address the situation of older
women, prepare youth for the future and promote good early
childhood development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
