<HEADLINE> Nigeria Approves Partial Privatization of Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
approved the partial privatization of the Nigerian Ports
Authority (NPA) in a bid to change the under-utilization of its
port facilities, the official News Agency of Nigeria said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Minister of Transport, Pestus Porbeni made the
remarks at the weekend in Port Harcourt, in southern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Porbeni said the government was trying to pave way for
investments in the ports, including leasing port facilities to
investors.
</P>
<P>
If investors were allowed to operate in the ports, more job
opportunities would be created and more ships would be attracted
to the ports, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged the NPA to ensure that investors were
encouraged. He also urged the NPA to enter into leasing
arrangement, saying that those against the on-going leasing
arrangements were ignorant of the fact that it was the only
option left for the government to bring port facilities out of
their idleness.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the privatization exercise is not
going down well with the Senior Staff Association of the NPA,
which insisted that it ought to have been consulted so that the
exercise would not lead to mass entrenchment in the port system.
</P>
<P>
Despite the opposition, the reform has already begun in the
Apapa port in Lagos, where some offices, warehouses and stacking
areas have been leased to private investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
