<HEADLINE> Clinton Says More Work Needed for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton, after meeting leaders of Israeli and Palestinian leaders
at the White House, said that progress has been made but there are
still a lot of work to do before reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that we all agree that we have made progress on the
path to peace," Clinton said during a photo opportunity with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat standing beside him.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a significant narrowing of the gaps between the
two parties across a wide range of issues that were in the
American initiative we've been working on for months," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton noted that "there is still a substantial
amount of work to be done until a comprehensive agreement can be
reached."
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters he have asked Netanyahu and Arafat to
come back again in mid-October while Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Ambassador Dennis Ross will go back to the Middle
East next week.
</P>
<P>
"Because I'm convinced that the two leaders and the people they
represent want an agreement, I have asked them to come back to the
United States in mid-October, with their teams, to do the
intensive work necessary to see if we can conclude this," said
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Albright and Ross will "try to see how much preparatory work
can be done to narrow the differences further and to agree on at
least the modalities for what we will do here in mid- October,"
added Clinton.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting of the three leaders, Clinton also met
privately with Netanyahu while Arafat returned to New York to
address the U.N. General Assembly. Arafat is expected to be back
to the White House to meet Clinton on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has been in an impasse because
the Israelis disagreed on a U.S. proposal that Israeli troops
withdraw from 13 percent of the West Bank, claiming it created too
much security risk for Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel agreed reportedly that it would withdraw from 13 percent
of the land if three percent of the territory was set aside as a
nature reserve, where security was provided by Israelis with
construction of Israelis or Palestinians banned.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu met in New York under the auspices of
Albright, the first one-one-one meeting they had in a year.
</P>
