<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year EFF $864 Mln for Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Monday announced the approval of a three-year credit
for Bulgaria equivalent to some 864 million U.S. dollars under the
Extended Fund Facility (EFF).
</P>
<P>
The credit is provided to support the government's medium-term
economic report program for July 1998 to June 2001. Of the total,
the equivalent of about 72 million dollars is made available
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The medium-term program targets strong growth, at 4 to 5
percent GDP growth per annum, a decline in inflation to about 5
percent per year by 2001 and a substantial decline in the public
and external debt burden. The external current account deficit
will be kept in the range of 3 percent of GDP, a level considered
sustainable based on conservative assumptions about inflows of
foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria joined the IMF in September 1990. Its quota is about
640 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF credit
currently totals about 983 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
