The FTSE 100 closed up 32.5 at 5,093.5, just below its 5,097.3
session best, set about half-an-hour before close.
</P>
<P>
Steady Asian markets and the Dow's resilience Friday to fears
of more hedge fund woes initially saw shares higher. But buying
support had evaporated by mid-morning. At one point, the FTSE 100
hit a session low of 5,022.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that with the end of the third quarter
approaching, some players had decided to sit tight in volatile
conditions.
</P>
<P>
"We are really just trading on the day-to-day stories which
affect stocks, like LTCM last week" the dealer said. "There are
still opportunities to buy at bargain prices."
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares moved higher in late afternoon
trade, lifted by Wall Street's strong start. The Xetra Dax closed
97.06 points higher at 4,681.47.
</P>
<P>
However, gains were tempered by a slide in utility stocks on
the possibility that the new Social Democratic majority may
increase energy taxes.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, shares shook off mid-session losses to move ahead on
the back of a bullish start to New York trade. The Cac 40 finished
25.1 points higher at 3,335.69.
</P>
<P>
Traders said news of a fall in overall demand for French
industrial goods in the past three months clouded sentiment.
</P>
