<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Says World Might Be Close to Depression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said here Monday the world might be
flirting with economic depression and warned that financial
operators must accept closer oversight.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister made the remarks as he was addressing the
general debate of the 53rd General Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
"We may be sliding toward worldwide recession. We may even be
on the edge of a global depression if urgent steps are not taken
through international collaboration and cooperation to halt the
slide and reverse the trend," said Badawi, whose country has been
badly battered by the turmoil affecting East Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis that "descended on East Asian countries
over a year ago" had brought social misery, political instability
and economic turmoil, Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
The rights of millions to live a life free from the scourge of
poverty and to have a decent standard of living with some basic
necessities had been "trampled by the manipulators of the currency
markets. Indeed, the super rich have impoverished the poor," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Badawi called for reform of international economic
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"There must be rules to encourage greater transparency.
Financial operators must abide by certain internationally accepted
regulations," he said. "They must accept closer supervision so as
to distinguish between genuine investors and currency
speculators."
</P>
<P>
A few developed countries on their own could not resolve the
problem and "cannot forever remain rich and prosperous if more
than two-thirds of the countries of the world remain poor and
socially and political unstable," Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
He voiced his welcome to a call by U.S. President Bill Clinton
for a conference in Washington on the financial and economic
crisis facing the world.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, in the absence of reforms or internationally
well-tested formula or guidelines, Malaysia has taken steps to
impose currency and capital controls to insulate its economy from
currency uncertainties while at the same time continue to be
active in international trade and continue to welcome foreign
investment," the foreign minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
