<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPP Agrees to Recount Unused Ballots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) agreed on Tuesday to recount all unused
ballots in the July 26 election in response to a demand by
the opposition Funcinpec party and the Sam Rainsy Party.(SRP)
</P>
<P>
The reconciliation was reached on Tuesday at the first
three-party negotiation in Phnom Penh. The three sides sent a
working team composed of seven members for the joint session and
told the press they had reached two agreements during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The first agreement is to ask the National Election Committee
(NEC) to recount all unused ballots in the July election. Second
is to reconvene the three-party working teams session on October 5
to elect the chairpersons of the National Assembly and nine
special committees.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec and the SRP are demanding a recounting of the
ballots and a review of the formula used to determine seat
allocations in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the two demands were not negotiable because
the opposition had dropped two other demands for recounting votes
and re-voting in certain parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The CPP and Funcinpec Monday briefly outlined their objectives
for the coalition negotiations. CPP politicians reiterated that
they expected their negotiations with Funcinpec would focus on
setting the new government in motion.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec announced three objectives in the coalition
negotiations: to ensure the National Assembly will function
fairly, to calm down outstanding election complaints and to
acquire amnesty for five Funcinpec officials.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Funcinpec and SRP staged a series of protests in
the capital. At least two people were reportedly killed in clashes
between protesters and police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
