<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Ministry of Transport and Communications
has decided to resume Cairo-Amman-Baghdad bus trips in two weeks,
which was suspended after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990,
Egypt's Alam Al Yom daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Chairman of the Arab Land Transport
Company Sami Fayed as saying that Egypt has reached an agreement
with two passenger companies of Jordan and Iraq on operating the
business.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The Beirut-based Arab Civil Aviation Organization
has decided to restore the membership of the Iraqi Airways, which
was suspended after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Airways General Manager Rabie Mohamed Saleh said that he
has met with Secretary General of the organization Abdul Wahab
Tufaha on the issue and the members of the organization have
agreed to restore Iraq's membership.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian Arab Bank has announced that it would
open two more branches in Beirut next year in a bid to expand its
business in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which has 10 branches in Lebanon, said the Central
Bank of Lebanon has approved its plan.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Netherlands will grant Jordan 1.66 million
Jordanian dinars (2.34 million U.S. dollars) under an agreement
signed here Tuesday between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The sum of money will cover 30 percent of the cost of a power
project near the Dead Sea, Jordan's official news agency Petra
reported. 
</P>
