<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Flight Misses in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A domestic flight of Sri
Lanka's private Lionair from Jaffna to Colombo, with 48 passengers
and four crew members on board, went missing within half an hour
after its departure Tuesday afternoon, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The flight which left the Palaly Airport in the Jaffna
peninsula at 1:45 p.m. (local time) did not reach Ratmalana
airport in Colombo as scheduled at 2:45 p.m., the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The plane's crew members include two Russian pilots and all the
passengers are civilians.
</P>
<P>
Lionair is one of the two private airlines which carry civilian
passengers from Colombo to the war-torn North Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The airline has been recently threatened by the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) who have been fighting a 15-year war
for a separate state.
</P>
<P>
It is not known whether the LTTE rebels had anything to do with
the disappearance of the Lionair flight, the sources added.
</P>
