<HEADLINE> U.S. Coach Search Awaits Queiroz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- If Carlos Queiroz agrees,
and can get out of his contract with the United Arab Emirates,
the well-respected coach from Portugal could be hired as the head
coach of the U.S. national soccer team.
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. Soccer Secretary General Hank Steinbrecher,
Queiroz, a Portuguese who recently completed a long awaited
report evaluating soccer in the United States, has yet to be
interviewed by USSF president Robert Contiguglia and is not easy
to interview.
</P>
<P>
"Carlos is in the middle of coaching right now," Steinbrecher
said. "They beat Qatar the other day."
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, an interview will occur, Steinbrecher said.
"Bruce Arena (D.C. United coach) may be favored but these things
continue to be fluid," Steinbrecher said.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. coach Bora Milutinovic, acquired by the New
York/New Jersey MetroStars, remains in the running, Steinbrecher
said, but Brazilian Carlos Alberto Parreira has dropped behind.
</P>
<P>
Steve Sampson's replacement likely will be chosen during the
Major League Soccer playoffs. The United States plays against
Australia on November 6 in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
If the new coach is not available then, Steinbrecher said,
Thomas Dooley could serve as player-coach or a national team
assistant could take over.
</P>
<P>
Also, the German Soccer Federation announced it will play the
United States on February 6, and Argentina on February 9 or 10.
</P>
