<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tactics Towards Iraq Changed, Says Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. ambassador to
Kuwait James Larocco said here Tuesday that the U.S. has not
changed its policy towards Iraq, but "the tactics have changed,"
the Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists and trainees at Kuna's Center for the
Development of Media Skills, Larocco reiterated that he hoped an
agreement would be reached between Iraq and the U.N. over weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Other options are not ruled out in case of a failure, he said.
</P>
<P>
The envoy said that the review of U.N. sanctions on Iraq will
take place "only if cooperation is resumed with the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM)" on eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
"We'll see where this goes. What we have declared now is that
if all of this fails, we will not rule out any options including
military options to force Iraqi compliance," Larocco added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq triggered the latest Iraqi-U.N. standoff by deciding on
August 5 to suspend cooperation with both IAEA and UNSCOM. The
Iraqi move led to a U.N. stop of its regular 60-day reviews of
economic sanctions on Iraq on September 9.
</P>
<P>
Larocco warned last Wednesday that Iraq's non-cooperation with
the U.N. will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. "was pursuing a diplomatic option at this
time and we will continue to do so," but added "there are no
options off the table."
</P>
<P>
Larocco was accompanying David Good, director of the Office of
North African, Near Eastern and South Asian Affairs at the United
States Information Agency, who delivered a lecture to journalists
at Kuna, on "U.S. Public Diplomacy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
