<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Speakers Focus on Globalization in General Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- As the 53rd General
Assembly session began the second week of its annual general
debate, high-level speakers called attention to the potential and
risks associated with economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
Sigapore's minister for foreign affairs, Shanmugam Jayakumar,
said the world should not turn its back on globalization. Rather,
the international community should come together to help countries
reap globalization's benefits. He said the United Nations should
continue to serve as a forum for dialogue on the subject.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Haji Ahmad Badawi called
for reform of the world's financial markets. "It has been said
that the markets would punish those countries which do not possess
proper financial structures and disciplines and which lack
transparency," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But the international financial market itself lacks
transparency," he said, adding that the 1.2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of currency bought and sold each day was under no global
surveillance system.
</P>
<P>
Domingo Siazon, the secretary of foreign affairs of the
Philippines, also addressed the "phenomenon of massive amounts of
capital flowing across national borders at lightening speed,
bloating economies into fragile bubbles as they rush in and
shaking economies to their foundations as they are withdrawn." He
said this aspect of globalization was fraught with risk and
required closer study.
</P>
<P>
James Michel, the vice-president of Seychelles, said that the
international community must extend support to developing
countries. In particular, he appealed to the European Union to
accept the request of the African, Caribbean and Pacific countries
for an extension of trade preferences under a World Trade
Organization waiver for a protracted period of time.
</P>
<P>
Jakaya Mrisho Kikwete, the minister for foreign affairs and
international cooperation of the United Republic of Tazania, said
that the establishment by the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund of the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries Initiative
had been a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed concern about the "conditionalities associated
with this initiative." He said that the criteria for that
initiative should be made more objective so that more least
developed countries could qualify.
</P>
<P>
Prince Mohamed Bolkiah, the foreign minister of Brunei
Darussalam, stressed that as the United Nations worked to reform
itself, efforts should be made to ensure that the world body
continued to work on behalf of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
The work of the United Nations in the field "gives the
organization meaning to billions," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Launch Campaign Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Health and Welfare
Ministry said Tuesday it would launch a six-month educational
campaign to spread information about AIDS and dispel myths
surrounding people inflicted with the disease.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said it would conduct presentations and pass out
educational materials at school festivals in high schools and
universities across the country, starting at Hokkaigakuen
University in Sapporo on October 11 and continuing through next
March.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials said they are targeting Japanese youth
because of the recent sharp increase in young people infected with
the disease.
</P>
<P>
The number of Japanese who contracted the HIV virus last year
totaled 268, of which 88 or 33 percent were in their twenties, up
17 percent from 1996, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has also prepared educational kits aimed at
teaching elementary school, junior high school and high school
students about AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
