<HEADLINE> AL Hails U.S. New Efforts in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid Tuesday hailed the U.S. offer to hold
a tripartite summit in Washington next month as a sign of its
continuous efforts in Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab world sees that holding a second trilateral summit in
Washington of U.S. President Bill Clinton, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu as a
necessary step towards overcoming a deteriorating Mideast peace
process," the AL chief told Egyptian Voice of Arabs in New York.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has invited Arafat and Netanyahu to return to
Washington in mid-October to try to wrap up a deal on the overdue
Israeli troops withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has called on Israel to hand over 13 percent more of
the West Bank land to the Palestinians in exchange for intensified
Palestinian efforts to fight Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has accepted the formula, and Israel
agreed to hand back 10 percent of the West Bank to full
Palestinian control, with an additional 3 percent turned into a
nature reserve in which Israel has full security control for the
time being.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Abdel-Meguid also affirmed the Arab solid
support of the palestinian people in their right for
self-determination and the establishment of their own state.
</P>
<P>
"U.N. Resolution 181 of 1947 called for the establishment of
two states, one Palestinian and one Israeli, and all Israeli
attempts to obstruct the establishment of this state are
unacceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
With Palestinian-Israeli peace talks deadlocked for 18 months
due to Israel's intransigence, Arafat has threatened to announce
the intention to unilaterally declare independence next May, a
deadline for the completion of the historic Oslo accords, when
addressing the U.N. General Assembly Monday.
</P>
<P>
But he stopped short of announcing his statehood threat Monday
after he met with Clinton and Netanyahu in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
