<HEADLINE> Hingis Beats Martinez in Grand Slam Cup Women's Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland's Martina Hingis
beat Conchita Martinez of Spain 6-2, 7-5 in the women's opening
game of the 6.7 million U.S. dollars Grand Slam Cup in Munich,
Germany, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, who turns 18 on Wednesday, needed one hour and 20
minutes to overcome the 26-year-old Spaniard and reach the
semifinals of the women's singles event.
</P>
<P>
Eight women are participating for the first time since the
inauguration of the cup in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The tournament nominally brings together players with the best
records in the four Grand Slam events of the year, which are the
Australian, French and U.S. Open and Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
But three men's Grand Slam champions of the year will miss the
tournament, including Wimbledon champion Pete Sampras of the
United States, U.S. Open winner Patrick Rafter of Australia and
Spain's Carlos Moya, the French Open champion.
</P>
<P>
Only Australian Open champion Petr Korda is among the 12 men
here.
</P>
<P>
In the opening men's match, Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden rallied
from a 5-1 deficit in the opening set to beat Tim Henman 7-5,
6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
