<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iraq to Expand Health Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Health cooperation between
Egypt and Iraq will expand in the period ahead "for the health of
the Iraqi citizen," Egyptian Health Minister Ismail Sallam Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister, who visited Baghdad last month and
performed operations on some Iraqi patients, made the remarks
following meeting with his Iraqi counterpart Omeed Medhat Mubarak,
who arrived here early in the day for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Sallam and Mubarak agreed during their talks on holding
meetings of a number of joint panels to explore prospects for
deepening health cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Health cooperation between the two countries has been conducted
in line with an agreement covering pharmaceuticals, prophylactic
medicine, medical training and exchange of expertise, according to
Sallam.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official praised the Egyptian humanitarian
assistance to his country which has been suffering under
eight-year U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian exports to Iraq in the light of the U.N.-Iraq
memorandum of understanding stood at 230 million dollars from
January till the end of August, which are composed of food,
medicines and other daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Cairo and Baghdad have witnessed noticeable
improvement recently when visits at high level have been exchanged.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program struck in 1996, Iraq
is permitted to sell a limited amount of oil every six months to
import food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program is an exception of the crippling economic sanctions
the U.N. Security Council imposed on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaohe River Valley Proved to be Cradle of Chinese Civilization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A group of noted Chinese
archeologists and historians have ascertained that the Liaohe
River Valley in north China, like the Yellow River Valley and the
Yangtze River Valley, is one of the cradles of Chinese
civilization.
</P>
<P>
This conclusion was recognized by more than 100 scholars and
experts from both home and abroad after the scientists completed
their explorations early this month of the cultural relics of the
Xiajiadian culture, the Post-Hongshan culture, and Yinhe Rock
paintings in the Liaohe River Valley.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the study of Chinese civilization merely focused
on areas from the south to the Great Wall and ignored the regions
north of the Wall, said Zhang Zhongbai, a well-known Chinese
archeologist. "That is a big mistake," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Chinese culture originated in three areas
including the north China region centered on the lower and middle
reaches of the Yellow River, the south China region centered on the
lower and middle reaches of the Yangtze River, and the northeast
China region of the West Liaohe River.
</P>
<P>
The West Liaohe River connects with the plains of northeast
China and the Mongolia Plateau. In the past 10,000 years, four
layers of cultures there included the Hongshan, Xiajiadian, Lower
Layer and Upper Layer, and the Qidan-Liao cultures.
</P>
<P>
Xue Zhiqiang, director of the Institute of North China Studies,
said that the West Liaohe River civilization which originated
8,000 years ago was earlier than the culture of Huangdi in
Chinese legend. The Hongshan Culture, which flourished abut 6,000
years ago, was made up of many tribes forming an ancient state in
the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that as early as 5,000 years ago, the Chinese culture
emerged in the Liaohe River Valley in northeast China and
gradually advanced with the building of temples.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, the Yellow River civilization represented
farming culture and the Yangtze River civilization was a
combination of farming and marine culture, but the Liaohe River
civilization was a manifestation of the transition from nomadic to
farming cultures.
</P>
<P>
Xue noted that the influence of the Liaohe River civilization
on the origins of Chinese culture was equal to that of the Yellow
River and Yangtze River valleys.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Day Reception Held in Guangzhou City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Over 400 people attended a
grand reception marking the 49th founding anniversary of the
People's Republic of China this evening in Guangzhou, capital of
south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The reception, hosted by the Guangzhou Municipal
People's Government, invited nearly 250 overseas guests from 31
countries and regions, including the United States, Japan, Poland
and Thailand.
</P>
