<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Withdraws Proposed Rule on Expression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Tuesday withdrew a proposed regulation in lieu of law on freedom
of expression, but said it would still submit a draft law on the
same matter.
</P>
<P>
"The draft would be submitted soon, as up to date the mechanism
for freedom of expression has not yet been regulated," Minister of
Defense and Armed Forces Commander Gen. Wiranto said at a plenary
session of the House of Representatives here.
</P>
<P>
He said expressing opinions is the right of everybody and every
group, as long as what is submitted to is a positive input, demand
or suggestion.
</P>
<P>
"But, now, there has been a drastic change where rallies have
turned out to be a pressing and forcing movement highlighted by
brutality, anarchy and other destructive things," he added.
</P>
<P>
Students in Jakarta and other cities held rallies almost every
day this month to protest against the spiraling prices of basic
commodities. They urged President B.J. Habibie to take concrete
measures to solve the economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes, the rallies were also exploited by a certain
interest that could not be controlled," Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Justice Muladi said the draft had been submitted to
the president for his signature prior to being conveyed further to
the House.
</P>
<P>
The official explanation of the draft will be delivered by the
government on October 2, he added.
</P>
<P>
The proposed regulation, submitted by the government to the
House of Representatives earlier this month, had got both positive
and negative responses from the people, especially concerning its
issuance and some of its contents.
</P>
<P>
House members had questioned the limitation to 50 of the number
of participants in rallies without approval and some other aspects
of the proposed regulation had also been questioned, including the
requirement for written approval and the time and place for the
expression as well as methods for dispersing such actions.
</P>
</TEXT>
