<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Navy to Strengthen Presence in Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Commander of the Iranian navy
Abbas Mohtaj announced here Tuesday that his force would
strengthen presence in the Caspian Sea, the official news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony arranged by the Ports and Shipping
Organization on the occasion of the International Seafaring Day,
Mohtaj said that having a stronger presence in the Caspian is
among the future programs of the navy.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Iran announced to build up its naval
force in the Caspian. Iranian government had repeatedly stated
that the Caspian should remain a "non-military zone," for the
benefit of peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mohtaj did not spell out the reasons behind Iran's new move in
the world largest inland waters, but he underlied the country's
need to "detect and deter threats."
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately clear how many troops the Iranian navy so
far deployed in the Caspian. Tehran had in the past focused its
attention on the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The disintegration of the Soviet Union, and the discovery of
oil and gas resources under the Caspian seabed, have brought up
disputes on how to share the resources among littoral states.
</P>
<P>
Iran holds that the resources should be commonly shared by all
the five littoral states, while Russia, Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan
and Azerbaijan prefer the division of the sea into national
sections.
</P>
<P>
Consultations among those neighbors are still underway to work
out a legal framework to solve their dispute over the Caspian.
</P>
<P>
Mohtaj added that the naval force of the Iranian Army and the
Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) had managed to restore
security in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 year, the Iranian Army and the IRGC have been
trying to guarantee security in the region, he said, the country
now enjoys full security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
