<HEADLINE> Flood-Fighting Heroes Speak to Audience of Nearly 10,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Eight people crowned
"Flood-Fighting Heroes and Models" spoke to an audience of nearly
10,000 about their experiences and heroic deeds during the
country's two-month-long battle against the worst flooding in
decades at the Great Hall of the People in downtown Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The speakers included officers of the People's Liberation Army
(PLA) and the armed police force, which mobilized over 300,000
soldiers and officers to participate in the flood-fighting and
rescue operations, officials from regions most severely hit by the
floods, and ordinary citizens who made outstanding contributions
to the flood-fighting endeavor.
</P>
<P>
One of the speakers was Wang Zhancheng, a handicapped man in
his late 60s and a citizen of Wuhan, capital of central China's
Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
On July 30, Wang, who has decades of flood-fighting experience,
used his own body to plug a one-meter gap in the city's
embankment. He was named the "Top Flood-Fighting Hero
of Wuhan".
</P>
<P>
Today's eight speakers are part of a newly formed lecturing
group, which has nine other members. The group plans to travel
around the Chinese capital to give more talks.
</P>
<P>
Today's event was jointly hosted by the Departments of
Publicity and Organization of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC)
Central Committee, the General Political Department of the PLA,
the CPC Beijing Municipal Committee, and other central departments.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yunshan, executive deputy head of the Publicity Department
of the CPC Central Committee, presided over today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
From July to September, severe flooding hit the vast Yangtze
River basin and then attacked northeast China's Nenjiang river and
Songhua river basins, affecting a dozen provinces and regions.
</P>
<P>
Government reports say that 3,004 people were killed nationwide
in the floods, and direct economic losses totalled some 20 billion
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
