<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Proposal Negative: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot government believes
the international community considers a Turkish Cypriot proposal
for a Cyprus confederation as negative, government spokesman
Chirstos Stylianides said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"A joint statement by the permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council and comments by U.S. officials now indicate
that the world community assumes a negative stance toward the
unacceptable Turkish position," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman has just returned from New York, where he
accompanied President Glafcos Clerides attending the U.N. General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash put forward a proposal
last August for the establishment of a confederation of two equal
states in Cyprus as "the only structure" of a settlement. The idea
has been rejected by Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The permanent members of the U.N. Security Council in a
statement last week reiterated that a political settlement in
Cyprus should be in accordance with the Security Council
resolutions, which provide for a bicommunal, bizonal federation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Clerides' meetings in New York, Stylianides said
it was an intensive week of meetings and the outcome of which will
be assessed by the island's political leadership at a meeting of
the National Council, the top advisory body to the president on
handling the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports about an arms sales agreement between
Turkey and Britain, Stylianides said the two countries have a
trade accord on defense matters, to which Cyprus does not object.
</P>
<P>
"What we are interested in is that Britain backs the
U.N. resolutions and supports Cyprus' right to self-defense and
Cyprus' right to move on with its accession course to the
European Union," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed troops and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been trying for decades to help
unify the divided island, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
