<HEADLINE> Lhasa's GSM Network Upgraded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The first phase of expansion of
the global system for mobile communications (GSM) network in
Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, has been completed
and the upgraded network began operating this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications authorities in Lhasa initiated the GSM
network in August 1997, but because of a shortage of funds
network capacity was only 4,000 users at that time, local
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The city had registered 3,600 GSM subscribers by the end of
April this year.
</P>
<P>
When the optical-fibre cable between Lanzhou, Xining and Lhasa
opened in August, Wu Jichuan, minister of Information Industry,
promised to help upgrade the region's GSM equipment.
</P>
<P>
Tibet then obtained 80 million yuan (about 9.64 million
U.S. dollars) in financial aid from the central telecommunications
authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
