<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Urges Speedy Rehabilitation Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina Tuesday asked the authorities concerned to relax and
simplify the approval procedure for projects relating to
post-flood rehabilitation, the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The directive came at a meeting of the Executive Committee of
the National Economic Council which approved eight projects with
an estimated cost of 14.6 billion taka (about 310.3 million U.S.
dollars) including project aid of over 7 billion taka (about 148.9
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed the need for giving top-most
priority to post-flood reconstruction and rehabilitation programs
to recoup the enormous losses caused by the devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
Hasina directed the Planning Commission to issue necessary
directives for speedy approval of various projects.
</P>
<P>
She also asked the authorities concerned to take into serious
consideration the effects of flood, cyclone, tidal surge, water
logging, river erosion and other natural disasters and calamities
while preparing designs for construction of bridges, culverts and
other infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
The 10-week-long flood, which started hitting the country in
early July, has affected 52 of the 64 districts, with nearly 30
million people seriously affected and the flood-related death toll
rising to more than 1,000. The preliminary economic loss is
estimated at about 3.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
