<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian
Qichen said today that the Chinese government is deeply concerned
about the attacks on Chinese-Indonesians which occurred in
Indonesia in May.
</P>
<P>
"We have noticed that the Indonesian government promised to
deal with the incident in a serious way," Qian said at a National
Day reception held by the State Council's Office of Overseas
Chinese Affairs, the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office and the
Taiwan Affairs Office.
</P>
<P>
"We hoped that the Indonesian side would handle the incident
properly as soon as possible and prevent such things from
happening again," he said.
</P>
<P>
For many years, the Chinese-Indonesians, together with
other Indonesians, have made indelible contributions to the
social and economic development of Indonesia, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Thus, they should be respected the same as other Indonesians
and should enjoy the same treatment and rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, their personal safety and just rights and interests
must be fully safeguarded by the Indonesian government, Qian added.
