<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Single Parents Head 14 Percent of EU Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 29 (Xinhua) -- There are nearly 7 million
single parents with dependent children in the European Union (EU),
or 14 percent of all EU families, Eurostat reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European
community said the number of single parents witnessed a large
increase over the 9 percent in 1983.
</P>
<P>
EU-wide, 84 percent of all single parents are women.
</P>
<P>
At 23 percent, Britain has proportionately the highest number
of single-parent families, whereas Greece has the lowest at 7
percent within the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
The rise in single parenthood has been one of the most striking
demographic and social trends in recent years, Eurostat said. From
1983 to 1996, the number of single parents rose by an average of
58 percent in the eight EU member states with available data.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 single parenthood data is the latest available in
Eurostat.
</P>
<P>
Single parents doubled in Ireland and rose by 94 percent and 75
percent in Britain and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The statistical bureau attributed the reason for the growing
number of single parents to a breakdown in marriages and births
outside of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
Single parents, according to Eurostat, face higher
unemployment, lower educational achievement and three-quarters the
income of two-parent families with dependent children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
