<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gets ADB Loan for Microfinance Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) said Tuesday that it has approved a 42.6-million-U.S.-dollar
loan to support the Bangladeshi government's efforts to reduce
poverty by providing microfinance services to the poor.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said in a press release that nearly half
a million impoverished households in rural areas in Bangladesh
will be organized into cooperatives to start their own enterprises
under an ADB-funded microfinance project.
</P>
<P>
The ADB will also provide a technical assistance grant of
800,000 dollars to help set up a pilot microcredit bank owned by
the poor.
</P>
<P>
Employment in the rural areas of Bangladesh is seasonal and
nearly half of the rural population is officially considered poor,
the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
The project will target disadvantaged women and will raise
their awareness and self-confidence by providing them with skills
to undertake income-generating activities and with credit to
develop microenterprises. 
</P>
