<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts New Classifications of Ownership Forms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The State Statistics Bureau
has adopted a new method classifying China's publically owned
and non-publically owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the new classifications aims to have accurate
knowledge of the ownership structure of Chinese enterprises, said
the bureau.
</P>
<P>
According to the bureau, the public economy includes firms
owned by the State and the collective, while the non-public
economy covers private firms, foreign funded firms, and companies
with investment from Hong Kong, Macao or Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The bureau noted that the former classifications adopted in
1992 are unable to reflect accurately the ownership structure of
China's economy and the proportion of the State-owned economy.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also issued two accessory rules recently on methods
of calculating into which category an enterprise properly should be
classified.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
