<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov Warns Against Regional Separatism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov warned regional leaders Tuesday of "the danger
of separatism" as the government plans to draft a law that would
sack what it describes as "separatism-mongering regional bosses."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of cabinet members and leaders of regions
concerned about the country's socio-economic situation, Primakov
said that only 50 percent of anticipated taxes were collected in
September, due in part to the suspension of tax payments by
regional governments to the federal coffer.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who assumed office two weeks ago and is still in the
process of filling slots in his cabinet, also pointed to the
shortage of consumer goods resulting from dwindling imports.
</P>
<P>
Following the previous government's August 17 decision to
devalue the ruble and default on some domestic and foreign debts,
the import of foods dropped more than 83 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
The national currency now stands at about 16 rubles to the
dollar, down 60 percent from the pre-crisis rate of 6.3 rubles to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
"This situation has undermined the available food stockpiles in
large industrial centers," Primakov said, adding that the
situation is aggravated by poor harvests.
</P>
<P>
He also warned of "political ambitions" in the planned October
7 national protest in the midst of rising social discontent.
</P>
<P>
"Political ambitions must not eclipse the main thing, the love
of the Homeland and desire to promote the well-being of all the
people of Russia," Primakov said. He expressed the hope that
organizers of the protest would "act with honest ends in view"
rather than "rock the boat."
</P>
<P>
"We must not tolerate any unlawful and anti-constitutional
actions such as the blocking of roads," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Coal miners blocked key railways around the country last
summer to demand payment of back wages, costing the country
millions of rubles. Authorities have threatened to bring charges
against organizers of blockades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
