<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Control of Capital Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China will further tighten
control over capital accounts, and any domestic enterprises
holding foreign-currency income capital accounts abroad without
state approval must transfer the money back to China before
October 1, a senior finance official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Wu Xiaoling, director of the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange, told a press conference that according to China's
existing foreign-exchange control regulations, foreign-exchange
incomes of domestic institutions, if not approved by the state,
must not be left abroad, and must be transferred back to China
in time.
</P>
<P>
"So what I announced today is not a new policy, but an attempt
to correct the illegal activities conducted by some enterprises
with capital accounts, and it has nothing to do with
normal capital funds of enterprises investing abroad," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Since the overwhelming majority of enterprises will abide by
the law in their business operations, she said, the amount of
capital illegally left abroad would not be large, and
bringing the money back should not have a major impact on
enterprises from the interior areas with investments in Hong
Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
