<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deposits Continue to Increase in HK in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Total deposits continued to
increase but domestic loans contracted in Hong Kong in August,
according to statistics released by the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Total deposits went up for the third straight month, growing by
1.4 percent in August after a 3.8-percent rise in the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
Both Hong Kong dollar and foreign currency deposits increased,
by 0.6 percent and 2.5 percent respectively. During the month, the
corporate sector continued to bring their offshore funds back to
Hong Kong, but the size of repatriation reduced.
</P>
<P>
Of the HK dollar deposits, demand and savings deposits fell by
2.9 percent and 3.9 percent respectively during the month while
time deposits rose by 2 percent. As the growth of foreign currency
deposits outpaced that of HK dollar deposits, the HK dollar share
of total deposits was lowered to 57.3 percent at end-August from
57.7 at end-July.
</P>
<P>
During the month, total loans and advances declined by 2.3
percent. Offshore loans remained on a downward trend, dropping by
5.8 percent. Domestic loans also decreased by 0.2 percent. Loans
for trade financing contracted further by 2.1 percent while other
loans for use in Hong Kong were flat.
</P>
<P>
As HK dollar deposits rose but HK dollar loans fell, the HK
dollar loan-to-deposit ratio decreased to 105.1 percent at
end-August from 106.2 percent at end-July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
