<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Discusses Troops in Macao SAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The stationing of troops by
China's central government in the future Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) was one of the major topics discussed
here Tuesday by chief representatives of both sides of the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG).
</P>
<P>
Han Zhaokang, chief of the Chinese side of the Sino-Portuguese
JLG, told reporters that China had notified Portugal of the
arrangements of troops stationing before Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side expects that the Portuguese side will make
cooperative efforts so that Chinese troops can enter Macao in time
after the Chinese government resumes sovereignty over Macao next
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The central government of China is to carry out its
responsibility of managing defense affairs in the Macao SAR as it
decides to send troops here in line with the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Declaration and the Macao Basic Law," Han said.
</P>
<P>
Santana Carlos, chief of the Portuguese side of the
Sino-Portuguese JLG, noted after the meeting that the Joint
Declaration does not make it clear that the Chinese central
government will station troops in Macao. He said it was not long
ago that Portugal had come to know what he called China's "new
stance."
</P>
<P>
Han responded that according to the stipulations in the
declaration and the Macao Basic Law, China's central government is
responsible for defense affairs in the Macao SAR. Therefore, the
stationing of troops falls into the category of China's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
When drawing up the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration, the
Chinese side had made explanations about the article concerning
Macao's defense affairs, making it explicit that the central
government has the right to station troops in the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the friendly relations between China and Portugal,
China had notified the Portuguese side of the stationing of troops
in advance (of a relevant announcement)," Han said. "But China
regards the stationing of troops as a matter within the sphere of
China's sovereignty and there is no need of consultation between
the two sides."
</P>
<P>
Now it is time for the Sino-Portuguese JLG to discuss the
concrete arrangements of troops stationing in the Macao SAR, Han
said.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting which lasted more than five hours, the two
chief representatives also talked about other major issues
concerning the power transfer of Macao, such as official languages
to be used in Macao, Macao's budget for 1999, the localization of
laws and allowances to senior civil servants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam PM Calls for Continued Renovation in Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai has called for overcoming economic difficulties and
maintaining stability in socio-economic development by continuing
renovation.
</P>
<P>
Khai made his call in a government report to a national
conference of the Provincial People's Committees and People's
Councils here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Khai listed major issues that the central government and local
authorities need to address in their socio-economic development
plan for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 socio-economic plan will focus on continuing the
renovation process, bringing into strong play domestic resources
to minimize negative effects of the regional economic crisis on
the national economy, maintaining stability in socio-economic
development, and keeping under control the slowdown of the growth
rate, said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said it is necessary to create favorable
conditions to rapidly develop a number of sectors for the rest of
this year and the next year.
</P>
<P>
The first task is to maintain socio-economic development
stability, focusing efforts on resolving problems which may cause
economic bankruptcy and decline, Khai said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the growth rate for 1999 will not stand as high as
that of 1998.
</P>
<P>
But the sectors of agriculture, forestry and aquatic products
processing, which are less affected by the crisis, and industries
and services employing large workforce and having outlets abroad
should be developed strongly to make up for the losses in other
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister set as major tasks to adjust the economy
while continuing to boost the renovation process in line with the
party's policies and guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The revision of the economic growth rate and major targets,
Khai said, is a solution aimed to create fundamental conditions
for the stable and sustainable development of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, the revision does not deflect the
development orientation of the country's socialist economy.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to review investment projects that are
underway, or that are expected to be implemented with state
fundings, Khai urged.
</P>
<P>
He said Vietnam should diversify the production of goods for
export to meet requirements of new markets in the future.
</P>
<P>
As a densely populated country, the domestic market is of great
potential, Khai said.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to increase the purchase power of the
population in general and those living in rural areas in
particular, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
