<HEADLINE> China Tightens Foreign Exchange Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China has taken measures to
strengthen management of foreign exchange, a senior government
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Wu Xiaoling, director of the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange (SAFE), told a press conference that a recent
nationwide foreign exchange inspection uncovered fake
customs reports involving several billions U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
She said that SAFE and other related government organizations
jointly launched a foreign exchange inspection in July to verify
the validity of customs reports valued above 200,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China has also prohibited Chinese banks from buying and
transferring foreign currencies for their customers in cities
other than the customers' locations.
</P>
<P>
She said, however, that foreign banks will be allowed to
continue conducting such business for the convenience of
foreign-funded enterprises in China.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China will adhere to the convertibility of its
currency under current accounts. She said the country will
guarantee the supply of foreign currencies for legal transactions,
debt repayment and normal capital flow and crack down on illegal
capital flow in foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
She reiterated that devaluation of the yuan will not be chosen
by China as a way to stimulate exports.
</P>
<P>
She said that "increasing domestic demand is a key" for China
to secure a fast growth rate.
</P>
<P>
"A country this big cannot rely on devaluation (of its
currency) to stimulate economic growth," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
