<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Opposition Party Agrees to Join Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Chart Pattana Party (CPP),
the third largest political party in Thailand, decided unanimously
at its meeting Tuesday to join the ruling coalition, paving the
way for a planned government reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held after the CPP meeting, CPP leader
Korn Dabbaransi said his party decided to join the ruling
coalition in a bid to help the government solve the problems the
country is facing.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Sanan Kachornprasart, secretary-general of the
Democrat Party, the core party in the coalition and Thailand's
second largest political party, went to the CPP headquarters to
offer a formal invitation to CPP, a major opposition party in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said at another press
conference that CPP's accession will be conducive to the
solidarity of the government.
</P>
<P>
The current coalition government consists of the Democrat
Party, Chart Thai Party, Social Action Party, Solidarity Party,
Seritham Party and 12 Prachakorn Thai Party members who defected
to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Holding 206 seats in the 389-strong parliament, the coalition
enjoys just a slender majority.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that at a time when the coalition was shaken by
the forced resignation of two health ministers of Social Action
Party over a hospital supplies scandal and the threat of expulsion
of 12 Prachakorn Thai Party rebels from their party, absorbing the
CPP into the coalition becomes extremely urgent.
</P>
<P>
Local television station Channel 9 reported that parties within
the ruling coalition welcomed the CPP's move, saying they are
willing to sacrifice some of their portfolios to the new comer.
</P>
<P>
As to which portfolios will go to the CPP, Sanan said it is to
be decided after negotiations among secretary-generals of all the
ruling parties.
</P>
<P>
Channel 9 predicted that the CPP will take about 10 posts,
including one deputy prime minister and portfolios of industry,
public health, labor and social welfare and minister of the prime
minister's office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
