<HEADLINE> S. Korean Stocks Up 2.15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Seoul's main index rose 6.6
points, or 2.15 percent, closing at 312.33 Tuesday due to seven
bank labor unions' retreat from a threatened strike and
expectations for a U.S. interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Turnout was 61.38 million shares worth 293.1 billion won (some
209 million U.S. dollars). Advancers outnumbered decliners 470 to
282, with 106 shares unchanged.
</P>
<P>
A strike would have hurt the financial markets, but news that
many bank unions were resuming normal operations boosted investor
confidence, market observers said.
</P>
<P>
Expectations for U.S. Federal Reserve's imminent announcement
on interest rate cuts, together with the South Korean government's
strong determination to revive the economy, also helped elevate
market sentiment, they said.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government's pledge Monday to inject 21
trillion won (some 1.4 billion dollars) into the financial sector
this month also encouraged both foreign and domestic investors to
buy more orders, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Monday, South Korean President Kim Dae-jung announced that his
government will expand the money supply and fiscal spending at the
expense of incurring a wider budget deficit, prop up domestic
consumption and lower interest rates while continuing fast and
effective reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
