<HEADLINE> Malaysian Opposition Leader Wants Anwar Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Parliament
opposition leader Lim Kit Siang Tuesday called for the release of
Former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim from detention under
the Internal Security Act (ISA).
</P>
<P>
Anwar should be freed "to prepare for his own self-defense" as
he has been charged in court with corruption and sodomy, Lim, who
is also Democratic Action Party secretary-general, told reporters
at the parliament lobby Tuesday, according to the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
"It is a mockery of justice for him to be charged and still
(detained) under the ISA. It is unfair of him to be in double
jeopardy," Lim was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was arrested under the ISA on September 20 following
riots by his supporters in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
He was produced in Sessions Court 4 at the Courts Complex here
Tuesday morning to face nine charges, five of corruption and four
for committing sodomy, to all of which Anwar pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was charged in the court with sodomizing an adopted
brother, his ex-driver and two others. Anwar, 51, is alleged to
have committed the offenses between March 1993 and April this
year.
</P>
<P>
He is accused of committing the offenses under Section 377B of
the Penal Code which provides for imprisonment up to 20 years and
whipping upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
The case was later transferred to the High Court for hearing on
a date to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Anwar told the Sessions Court that he was beaten by police
while being held in the Bukit Aman lockup here.
</P>
<P>
Judge Hasnah Mohd Hashim allowed Anwar's application made via
his counsel Christopher Fernando to complain about the injuries he
sustained while in police custody.
</P>
<P>
When approving the application, the judge said the case had
been transferred to the Kuala Lumpur High Court and the Sessions
Court was merely recording the complaints.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was allowed by the Sessions Court earlier to be examined
by an independent doctor to be appointed by his family.
</P>
<P>
Hasnah said Anwar's complaints were limited to the injuries he
sustained to his left eye.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's wife, Wan Azizah Wan Ismail, two of their daughters and
Anwar's father and father-in-law were present in court Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Clad in brown pants and a checkered shirt, Anwar was smiling as
he entered the courtroom. He then embraced his wife, his daughters
and his father.
</P>
<P>
Besides the nine charges mentioned at the court, one more
charge of unnatural sex act against Anwar will be mentioned at the
Petaling Jaya court near here Wednesday, said an announcement by
the Attorney-General's Chambers earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement signed by Special Officer to the
Attorney-General, Shamsuddin Hassan, the attorney-general as the
public prosecutor was satisfied that there was sufficient "prima
facie" evidence to charge Anwar with the offenses.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was dismissed as deputy prime minister and minister of
finance on September 2 and expelled from the ruling United Malays
National Organization the following day for "low morals."
</P>
<P>
Anwar's supporters had held several assemblies in the Jalan
Raja courthouse area here since his detention, forcing police to
impose tight security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
