<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Criticizes U.N. Resolutions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 29 (Xinhua) -- There is a certain
incompatibility in various U.N. resolutions on Iraq, with one
imposing sanctions, another imposing a humanitarian program, said
a senior U.N. official on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Denis Halliday, the outgoing U.N. humanitarian coordinator for
Iraq, made the remarks at a press conference here when talking
about reasons for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
"One U.N. resolution imposes sanctions, and another imposes a
humanitarian program with all of its shortcomings and politics
trying to counter the first resolution, ... as representative of
the United Nations, I have to deal with that," said Halliday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official also admitted that he "has had difficulties
in the relationship" between the U.N. headquarters and his mission
in Iraq, but stressing that this "is an established phenomenon"
and should not be exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on U.N. Resolution 986 which allows Iraq to sell
limited amount of oil to buy back humanitarian supplies for its
suffering people, Halliday said "none of us wanted 986."
</P>
<P>
However, he said that under circumstances of sanctions, this
humanitarian program "is modestly working and does make a
difference."
</P>
<P>
Halliday, at the U.N. assistant secretary-general level, is
one of the U.N. senior officials who are strongly advocating the
lifting of sanctions on Iraq imposed after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Halliday told the press conference that he has been invited to
go to Washington next week to brief some 40 members of
U.S. Congress in a panel discussion.
</P>
<P>
"This will give me an opportunity to brief important
decision-makers in Washington as to the impacts the sanctions
have had here in Iraq in terms of the economy of the country and
most important of all, of course, the people and the children of
this country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Halliday, a national of Ireland, also cited a personal reason
for his resignation from the post he has taken for 13 months.
</P>
<P>
"I have a lovely 15-year-old daughter, and I would like to go
back to spend some time with her because she grows up completely
and goes off to university," he said with emotion.
</P>
<P>
Halliday will leave here on Wednesday. U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has appointed Hans von Sponeck, a national of Germany
to succeed Halliday.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck will leave his current post as regional representative
and director of European affairs at the U.N. Development Program's
office in Geneva and take up his new duties in Baghdad towards
the end of October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
