<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Researchers Claim New Bioformulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Agricultural
Research Institute based here said it has developed two
eco-friendly bioformulations that are not only effective against a
number of crop-damaging fungi but will also increase crop yield.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Tuesday that both the
formulations, named Kalisena SD and Kalisena SL, were prepared
from the AN 27 strain of aspergillus niger, a black-colored fungus
present naturally in soil.
</P>
<P>
The kalisena (black army) formulations are mixtures of an
anti-fungal compound and two growth promoters present in
aspergillus niger, said PTI.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the institute claimed that the mixtures are
effective against six soil fungi which cause widespread damage to
various crops.
</P>
<P>
What made them superior to conventional applications is that
only a single application of Kalisena SD to seeds and Kalisena SL
to nurseries is needed to control fungi, said Bineeta Sen, leader
of the research team from the institute's Department of Plant
Pathology.
</P>
<P>
Besides, they have a prolonged shelf-life of two years which is
not offered by any other bioformulations and are safe for use, she
added.
</P>
<P>
Farm trials carried out by the institute's scientists in 10
states against different crop diseases have proven kalisena's
efficacy, according to Sen.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that soil pathogens are responsible for 25
percent of annual crop loss due to diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Reaps Good Rice Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has got a bumper
rice harvest this year for the third consecutive year with
production reaching 35.6 million sok, or 5.1 million tons, the
Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although it dropped 5.8 percent from the 37.8 million sok of
rice yield in 1997, this year's figure shows a five percent more
than the ministry's 1998 target of 33.9 million sok.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rice production per 100 square meters was
tallied at 485 kilograms, exceeding the annual average of 470
kilograms achieved in 1993-1997, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the rice harvest to high temperatures
and good weather since late August, and efforts by the government
and farmers to secure more rice-cultivating areas and develop
high-quality paddies.
</P>
<P>
South Korea transformed about 4,000 hectares of idle land and
3,000 hectares of reclaimed land into paddy fields this year. The
paddy fields decreased an annual average of 21,000 hectares in
1992-1997.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the total area of paddy fields jumped 7,000
hectares from a year earlier to 1.06 million hectares in 1998.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's rice stockpiles are expected to increase from 6.5
million sok at the end of October this year to 7.3 million sok at
the end of next October, surpassing the optimum level of 5.5-5.8
million sok recommended by the Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO), the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
