<HEADLINE> Egyptians, Libyans Asked to Leave Somalia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Six break-away political
organizations from Somalia's numerous political factions issued
an ultimatum demanding the representatives of Egypt and Libya to
leave Somalia as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, the political factions threatened that
they will not shoulder the responsibility of the consequences
when their orders are not obeyed.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Hajji Bod, former Vice Chairman of Ali Mahdi Mohamed
faction and one of the signatories of this statement, said they
are going to give the Egyptian and Libyan representatives no more
than 48 hours to leave Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The statement has accused the diplomats for re-arming and
supporting Ali Mahdi Mohamed and Hussein Mohamed Aidid factions.
</P>
<P>
The statement which was issued after a meeting by the
break-away faction leaders Monday also condemned what they called
the alliance of Hussein Mohamed Aidid and Ali Mahdi Mohamed
factions for carrying out what is termed as various inhuman
actions in four locations, three in Mogadishu and an alleged
attack against five villages in Bay region.
</P>
<P>
What prompted the strongly-worded statement is not known,
however the statement came shortly after the Egyptian ambassador
to Somali, Mohamud Mustafa, had made a donation of few boxes of
medicine against malaria to the administration of Mogadishu led
by Hussein Ahmed Ali.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Libya are among the outspoken countries from the
Arab League trying to support the disputed administration of
Mogadishu in accordance with the Cairo peace deal signed in
December last year. 
</P>
