<HEADLINE> Former Malaysian Deputy PM Claims Police Beat Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Former Malaysian deputy
prime minister Anwar Ibrahim told the Sessions Court here Tuesday
that he was beaten by police while being held in the Bukit Aman
lockup here following his arrest under the Internal Security Act
on September 20.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said this before Judge Hasnah Mohd Hashim after she
allowed his application made via his counsel Christopher Fernando
to complain about the injuries he sustained while in police
custody.
</P>
<P>
When approving the application, the judge said the case had
been transferred to the Kuala Lumpur High Court and the Sessions
Court was merely recording the complaints.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was allowed by the Sessions Court earlier to be examined
by an independent doctor to be appointed by his family.
</P>
<P>
Hasnah said Anwar's complaints were limited to the injuries
recorded by the court that is in relation to the injuries he
sustained to his left eye.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was Tuesday charged in the same court with sodomizing an
adopted brother, his ex-driver and two others. Anwar, 51, is
alleged to have committed the offenses between March 1993 and
April this year.
</P>
<P>
He is accused of committing the offenses under Section 377B of
the Penal Code which provides for imprisonment up to 20 years and
whipping upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was produced in Sessions Court 4 at the Courts Complex in
Jalan Raja Tuesday morning to face the nine charges, five of
corruption and four for committing sodomy, to all of which Anwar
pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
The case was later transferred to the High Court for hearing on
a date to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's wife Wan Azizah Wan Ismail, two of their daughters,
Anwar's father and father-in-law were present in court when the
case was mentioned Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Clad in brown pants and a checkered shirt, Anwar was smiling as
he entered the courtroom. He then embraced his wife, his daughters
and his father.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was arrested by police on September 20 under the Internal
Security Act following riots by his supporters here.
</P>
<P>
Besides the nine charges mentioned at the court here, one more
charge of unnatural sex act against Anwar will be mentioned at the
Petaling Jaya court near here Wednesday, according to an
announcement by the Attorney-General's Chambers earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement signed by Special Officer to the
Attorney- General, Shamsuddin Hassan, the attorney-general as the
public prosecutor was satisfied that there was sufficient "prima
facie" evidence to charge Anwar for the offenses.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was sacked as deputy prime minister and minister of
finance on September 2 and expelled from the ruling United Malays
National Organization (UMNO) the following day for "low morals".
</P>
<P>
Anwar's supporters had held several illegal assemblies in the
Jalan Raja courthouse area here since his detention forcing police
to impose tight security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
