<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Current Account Surplus Falls in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's current account
surplus registered 2.26 billion U.S. dollars in August, down 37
percent from the previous month's 3.61 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The fall was the first time in the past eight months due to
falling exports and growing interest payments for the country's
foreign debts, the Bank of Korea said Tueaday.
</P>
<P>
On a custom-cleared basis, South Korean exports decreased for
the fourth consecutive month to 9.82 billion dollars in August
while imports tumbled 38 percent to 7.12 billion dollars due to
shrinking domestic demand, reflecting the ongoing deepened
recession in the country.
</P>
<P>
The strike at Hyundai Motor Co., Russia's moratorium
declaration and seasonally sluggish industrial output in August
were also factors causing downing exports, said the central bank.
</P>
<P>
In terms of interest rate payments, South Korea registered a
substantial deficit of 250 million dollars resulting from interest
payments to the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest figure brought up the nation's current
account surplus for the year through August to a relatively
healthy 27.8 billion dollars, compared with the 5 billion
dollars deficit in the same time of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The surplus for the year is likely to surpass the initial
target of 37 billion U.S. dollars," said a spokesman of central
bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman has signed
an ordnance removing import duty on tomatoes for the duration of
the Jewish holiday season, which will last into mid-October, the
Jerusalem Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken after tomato prices skyrocketed because
of a shortage of supply, which was caused by the recent heat
waves.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury believes the temporary move will lead to a 20
percent to 30 percent cut in prices, which currently average some
11 shekels (about 2.86 U.S. dollars) a kilogram.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate stood at 9.1 percent in
July, a slight increase from 9 percent in both May and June, the
Jerusalem Post quoted official figures as reporting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Central Bureau of Statistics said that
although the unemployment rate growth slowed down, the growing
trend will continue for a few months.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index, meanwhile, increased at an annual 6
percent in July and August, compared to 4 percent in May and June,
the figures show.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The exports of Israel's software industry topped 1
billion U.S. dollars last year, according to a comprehensive
survey of the industry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the survey showed that software exports during the
first six months of 1998 reached 700 million dollars, representing
an increase of 20 to 25 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
North America was the most important market for Israel's
software products, absorbing 38 percent of the total exports;
Western Europe was just behind, with 37 percent of the market. The
East Asia and Southeast Asia accounted for 9 percent of the
purchases.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- As the service trade became a major area of activities
in the world, Egypt's share of it is still modest, Egyptian
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmad Gowaili said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide service exports in 1996 reached 1,260 billion
U.S. dollars against 5,000 billion dollars for the commodities
exports, said Gowaili at the inaugural session of a seminar here
on real estate and tourist investment.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's share of service trade in the world is still modest as
it ranges at merely between 7 to 8 billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds of the Suez Canal, the remittances of the Egyptian
expatriates and tourism constitute the major part of it, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwait Company for the Development of Small
Projects announced that it would establish more projects to
attract small Kuwaiti investors, the Kuwait News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The company's board chairman Adnan Al-Sultan told a news
conference here that his company had established five projects
with a total capital of 1 million Kuwaiti dinars (3.3 million
U.S. dollars) and had received 100 investors.
</P>
<P>
Sultan said the projects included two industrial businesses,
two handicraft ones and a commercial one.
</P>
<P>
Sultan pointed out that the small investors must meet certain
company requirements, namely, being a Kuwaiti national, having an
acceptable experience on the proposed activity, with a
contribution of at least 50 percent of a project's capital, which
must not exceed 1.5 million dinars (4.95 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition to financial assistance, the company will provide
small investors with strategic help to guarantee the success of
the projects, Sultan added.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait Company for the Development of Small Projects was
established by the Kuwaiti Public Authority for Investment in
June, 1998 with 100 million dinars (330 million dollars) for
managing national investment portfolios. 
</P>
</TEXT>
