<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Social Action Party Leader Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Montri Pongpanich, leader of
the Social Action Party (SAP), the third largest party in the Thai
ruling coalition, announced Tuesday to resign over the difference
within the party, television station Channel 9 reported.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by Channel 9, Montri said that there is no unity in his
party as it has been divided by different factions.
</P>
<P>
Montri, who will be replaced by SAP Secretary-General Suvit
Khunkitti, said that now as an ordinary SAP member, he will still
back his party to stay within the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that some of the SAP members have voiced their
will to withdraw from the six-party coalition, which enjoys just a
slender majority in the 389-strong parliament.
</P>
<P>
The current coalition government consists of the Democrat
Party, Chart Thai Party, Social Action Party, Solidarity Party,
Seritham Party and 12 Prachakorn Thai Party members who defected
to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of Montri as SAP leader is a prelude to an
inevitable major reshuffle of the Chuan Leekpai government.
</P>
<P>
The coalition has invited the opposition Chart Pattana Party
(CPP), the third largest political party in Thailand which holds
51 seats in the lower house, to join the government in a bid to
consolidate its majority.
</P>
<P>
However, CPP leaders have not given a reply to the coalition's
open arms, saying they will hold a party meeting to make a
decision.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, also leader of the Democrat
Party, core party in the coalition, had preferred a limited
change. However, growing dissatisfaction with two resigned SAP
ministers and the endangered career of 12 Prachakorn Thai rebels
have forced him to accept a wider reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Public Health Minister Rakkiat Sukthana and
his deputy Thirawat Siriwansan, both SAP members, were forced to
step down over the scandal that the ministry has forced hospitals
to buy medical equipment at inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
And the 12 Prachakorn Thai rebels are facing threat of
expulsion from their party and thus lost their status as
legislators.
</P>
<P>
Now the ruling parties are waiting for an answer from the CPP.
If the CPP accepts the invitation, every party in the coalition
has to sacrifice some of their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
However, Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda, a Democrat,
said his party will not give up the key economic portfolios so
that the work on the economic crisis could go on undisrupted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
