<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Efforts on Human Rights: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman
Tang Guoqiang said here today that China's decision to sign up the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights demonstrates
once again the country's determination to promote and protect
human rights.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan announced on September 23
at the 53rd session of the UN General Assembly that China will
sign up the covenant in early October. China signed up the
International Covenant on Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights
last October.
</P>
<P>
"China is willing to work with other countries to continue
efforts in promoting the cause of human rights," Tang said at
today's routine press conference.
</P>
<P>
China has always attached importance to the positive role the
international human rights covenant played in promoting and
protecting human rights, the spokesman said, adding that China has
signed up 17 international covenants on human rights.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese government respects human rights, and
has adopted legislative, judiciary and administrative measures
to promote and protect people's economic, social, cultural, civil
and political rights.
</P>
<P>
Since the initiation of reform and opening-up 20 years ago,
China's democratic and legal construction has witnessed great
improvement, and the legal protection of people's various rights
has been continuously reinforced, said Tang.
</P>
<P>
According him, in recent years, China has made greater strides
in legislation, and the Chinese National People's Congress and its
Standing Committee have passed a series of important laws
concerning labor, education, national compensation, prison,
judges, procurators, police, and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Especially from 1996 to 1997, China revised and amended its
Criminal Proceeding Law as well as the Criminal Law, which greatly
improved the legal protection over human rights.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government, while developing economy, will also
make unremitting efforts to develop democracy, reinforce legal
construction, and guarantee the human rights of its citizens, Tang
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
