<HEADLINE> Cambodian Parties Hold Three-way Coalition Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's main political
parties met here Tuesday afternoon to begin negotiations on
forming a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, attended by representatives from Cambodian
People's Party (CPP), Funcinpec Party and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP),
is expected to set a preliminary agenda for ongoing coalition
talks and outline procedures to be followed at Wednesday's
National Assembly meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 122-member parliament, which was sworn in Thursday in the
northern town of Siem Reap, is expected to begin work on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The seven-member Funcinpec team was led by General Secretary
Tol Lah, and included Rural Development Minister Hong Sun Huot,
Co-Interior Minister You Hockry and Cambodia's envoy to the U.N.,
Prince Sisowath Sirirath.
</P>
<P>
The six-member CPP delegation was led by Co-Interior Minister
Sar Kheng, and included cabinet head Sok An, Co-Defense Minister
Tea Banh and Secretary General Say Chhum.
</P>
<P>
The SRP's seven-member delegation included Vice General
Secretary Meng Rita and Sam Rainsy's legal advicer U. Bunlong.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the two major parties disputed on whether Sam Rainsy
Party (SRP) would be represented. Funcinpec officials said they
would follow the advice of King Sihanouk, who said last week that
the coalition talks should involve all three parties.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the King will leave Siem Reap for Beijing
on October 5 to have regular health check.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the CPP and Funcinpec briefly outlined their
objectives for the coalition negotiations. CPP politicians
reiterated that they expect their negotiations to meet with
Funcinpec counterparts to focus on getting the next government
going.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec has three objectives in the coalition
negotiations: ensure the National Assembly will function fairly,
resolve outstanding election complaints and amnesty requests for
five Funcinpec officials and work on the formation of government.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Funcinpec and SRP threatened to boycott
parliament in protest of alleged violation in the July 26
election. They staged more than a month of protests in the capital
during which at least two people were reportedly killed in clashes
between protesters and police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
