players were sidelined due to uncertainty over the market's
immediate direction.
</P>
<P>
The market trend continued to be mixed with trading lethargic
as lawmakers debated the amendments and reform of Malaysia's
securities industry regulations, according to dealers.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index was 9.75
points lower at 377.52, the all-share Emas Index shed 2.02 points
to 100.25, the Industrial Index dropped 16.48 points to 747.93 and
the Second Board Index lost 0.78 of a point to 93.35.
</P>
<P>
Losers overwhelmed gainers by 405 to 150 while 130 counters
were unchanged and 263 counters untraded.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover stood at 118.782 million shares worth
178.296 million ringgit (46.92 million U.S. dollars) from last
Friday's 120.133 million shares valued at 187.521 million ringgit
(49.347 million U.S. dollars) .
</P>
<P>
The main board turnover declined to 113.917 million shares
valued at 170.480 million ringgit (44.863 million U.S. dollars)
from 115.189 million shares worth 178.918 million ringgit (47.083
million U.S. dollars) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover stood at 4.865 million shares worth
7.816 million ringgit (2.056 million U.S. dollars) from 4.944
million shares valued at 8.603 million ringgit (2.263 million U.S.
dollars) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Off market turnover increased to 7.408 million shares worth
12.238 million ringgit (3.22 million U.S. dollars) from last
Friday's 1.727 million shares valued at 4.566 million ringgit
(1.202 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 5.279
million shares traded on the Main Board, industrial products
10.915 million shares, construction 11.160 million shares,
trading/services 34.911 million shares, infrastructure 520,000
shares, finance 16.658 million shares, hotels 383,000 shares,
properties 17.902 million shares, plantation 4.042 million shares,
mining 514.200 shares, trusts 94,000 shares, closed/fund 419,000
shares and loans 11.117 million shares. 
