<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Economy Faces Greater Challenges: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai said here on Monday that the country's economy is facing
"greater challenges" due to natural disasters and the negative
impacts of regional financial and currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Khai made the remarks in a government report he delivered to a
national conference of the provincial People's Committees and
People's Councils here.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 10 years of renovation, Vietnam has scored great
achievements in the economic field, with its gross domestic
product up by nearly 8.5 percent annually in the 1991-1997 period,
Khai said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, while entering 1998, Vietnam's economy has
to face "great difficulties and challenges," including the heavy
losses in agriculture, forestry and fishery caused by bad weather.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister also stressed that the Vietnamese
government has taken measures to overcome the difficulties,
control the slowdown in production and business, keep the growth
rate at between 6.1-6.3 percent, and stabilize its macro-economic
scale. 
</P>
