<HEADLINE> 10,000 Somali Refugees Return Home from Eastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A total of 10,000 Somali
refugees in Eastern Ethiopia have volunteered to return to their
homeland, the Ethiopian Herald reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Tsegaye Mehretu, Head of Eastern
Coordination Office of the Refugees and Returnee Department, as
saying that the refugees moved out from their refugee camp in
Teferi Ber in August and September to return to their hm town
of Guroma in north Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Tsegaye said that this brings to 40,000 the total number of
refugees repatriated since last January.
</P>
<P>
The Somali refugees have camped in Eastern Ethiopia following
civil war in Somalia in 1988 and the subsequent clan conflicts
between 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
Over 200,000 Somali refugees have been camped in Eastern
Ethiopia, according to figures released by the Office of United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).  
</P>
