<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Renews Call for Preferences for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard Tuesday repeated his call for all Australian voters,
including One Nation (Party) supporters, to send their preferences
to his coalition in a bid to get enough votes for re-election.
</P>
<P>
"I ask all Australians who don't vote for either the coalition
or the Labor Party, to think of the outcome if they vote for the
(opposition) Labor Party," he told reporters in Queensland state,
where the support for Pauline Hanson's One Nation Party is
stronger than the national average.
</P>
<P>
"And if people voting for minor parties - be it the Greens, be
it the Democrats, be it One Nation, be it anybody else - if they
don't want a Labor government then they should take care, no
matter what their preferred party's how-to-vote-card says, to
direct their preferences to the coalition," he said.
</P>
<P>
The renewed appeal for preferences came as the latest opinion
poll, which was published Tuesday in the national newspaper The
Australian, shows the support for both the ruling Liberal Party
and National Party coalition and the Labor Party is still
neck-and-neck.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll conducted last weekend, the coalition
gained only 43 percent of the primary votes and the Labor Party
won 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the Labor has retained an election-winning lead on the
two-party preferred vote, making the distribution of One Nation
preferences vital to the October 3 poll outcome.
</P>
<P>
As 47 out of a total of 148 Lower House seats are marginal and
neither the coalition nor the Labor is expected to gain more than
50 percent of the primary votes, the second preferences would
decide who is the winner of the election.
</P>
<P>
Under Australia's preferential voting system, voters are
required to rank candidates representing different parties or
groups in order of preference on the ballot papers. To be elected,
a candidate must achieve an absolute majority, namely, at least 50
percent plus one vote, either on first preference or following
distribution of preference votes.
</P>
<P>
If no candidate has more than half of the votes, the candidate
with the fewest votes is excluded. This excluded candidate's votes
are transferred to the other candidates according to the second
preferences shown by voters on the ballot papers.
</P>
<P>
This process of excluding candidates one by one, continues
until one candidate has more than half the total votes and is
declared elected.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Howard last week called on voters to direct the
second preferences to his coalition if they refuse to direct their
first ones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
