<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
ended stronger Tuesday, shrugging off earlier losses on the back
of a solid performance by Australia's telecommunications giant
Telstra and other industrial stocks.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index climbed 12.0 points to
2,603.6, off an intra-day low of 2,570.0.
</P>
<P>
However, brokers said investors remained cautious, sticking
with so-called safe-haven stocks ahead of the meeting of the
Federal Open Markets Committee, which is expected to announce a
rate cut of at least 25 basis points in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 266.01 million shares valued at
583.48 million U.S. dollars. Rises narrowly outpaced falls by 474
to 448, with 395 stocks steady.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index firmed 23.6 points, or half a
percent, to 4,565.6 while the all resources index edged up 2.1
points to 1,022.4.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts surged 20 Australian cents, or 4.3
percent, to 4.81 Australian dollars on volume of 21.77 million
shares worth 61.27 million U.S. dollars, placing it at the top of
the turnover table.
</P>
<P>
Diversified miner BHP forfeited eight cents to 12.27 Australian
dollars, global miner Rio Tinto moved up six cents to 20.26
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index gave up 3.3 points to 1,143.2 despite the spot
price of bullion selling in Sydney 2.90 U.S. dollars an ounce
better at 296.60 U.S. dollars per fine ounce by 15:20 Australian
Eastern Standard Time.
</P>
<P>
Australia's big four banks had mixed fortunes, with National
Australia Bank tumbling 37 cents to 20.66 Australian dollars,
Commonwealth Bank of Australia firming 24 cents to 20.13
Australian dollars, Westpac bank slipping eight cents to 9.50
Australian dollars, and ANZ bank gaining 8.3 cents to 9.10
Australian dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
