<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Firmer on U.S. Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
stronger Tuesday as financial markets around the world prepared
for an interest rate cut in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee (FOMC) will
meet early Wednesday morning (Australian Eastern Standard Time).
</P>
<P>
Glen Howard, an expert at Perpetual Funds Management, said a
boost in the price of gold helped the local currency sustain its
gains.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 59.78 U.S. cents from 58.85
U.S. cents at Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
Howard said if the U.S. committee decides to cut interest rates
the Australian dollar would be traded at 60.00 U.S. cents level
again.
</P>
<P>
An FOMC meeting that resulted in no interest rate cut could
have adverse effects on the market, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was buying 80.40 Japanese yen from 79.92 yen
Monday and 1.0003 German marks from 0.9916 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
