<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Descendant of Chinese Bankers Revives the Family Tradition (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Mao Minghui, a 31-year-old
antique shop owner in China's Shanxi Province, is a descendent of
China's earliest banker, and reflects the old family spirit.
</P>
<P>
He earns 200,000 yuan annually, 41 times the annual income of
an ordinary worker, from the antique shop, which is on the site of
the money exchange that dealt in loans and money changing, opened
by his forefathers.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of visitors come here because of the name and
prestige of my family," he says proudly. "My great great
grandfather, Mao Honghui, opened the first money exchange in China
on Western Street in the city of Pingyao 170 years ago."
</P>
<P>
In its heyday, it had more than 400 branches across China, and
dominated the financial sector in China. It also had agencies in
Russia, Mongolia, Japan and Korea. Southern Street alone had 22
banks and was known as the "Wall Street" of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
However, the old family banking business declared bankruptcy in
the 1930s as a result of the great increase in the number of
foreign financial institutions in China and the failure to shift
to more modern methods.
</P>
<P>
For quite a long time afterwards, the descendants of this
notable family had to live on less than 100 yuan a month and
couldn't even afford the maintenance costs of the houses they had
inherited.
</P>
<P>
"I was lucky to live in the days of reforms," Mao says, "in
recent years, the local government has had a series of
preferential land use, loan, and tax policies to encourage the
descendants of local traders to carry on the family line."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0169 </DOCNO>
