<HEADLINE> Polio, Ebola May Spread out of Africa: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Diseases such as polio and
even the dreaded Ebola virus could strike the rest of the world
from Africa unless vaccination efforts keep rolling, a UN health
official has warned.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim Samba, regional director of the World Health
Organization (WHO) for Africa, joined U.S. Surgeon-General David
Satcher in warning that Africa's vaccination campaign may be
starting to falter, the East African Standard newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Samba noted that some outbreaks of Ebola, a highly contagious
virus that causes haemorrhage, killed 70 percent of its victims
and polio once killed two million people a year.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the extraordinary progress toward polio eradication,
progress in Africa has not kept pace with progress in other
regions," Satcher was also quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
WHO, which hopes to eliminate polio by 2000, says some
countries are not contributing as much as needed.
</P>
<P>
He said that conflicts in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo, Liberia, Sierra Leone and some other African countries had
badly interfered with the vaccination program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
