<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Descendants Of Chinese Bankers Revives the Family Tradition (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Southern Street is now a busy shopping center with 73 stores,
60 of them involved in the antique business. Together, they do
300,000 yuan in business daily, and have become the largest
antique market in Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a government policy to diversify the economy, the
number of private businesses in Pingyao have gone from a dozen in
the early 1980s to more than 10,000 now in retail sales, food
processing, coal, textiles, and transport. The taxes paid by these
companies accounted for 18 percent of the county's annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
Mao signed a 10-year land lease with the local government, with
no rent for the first two years, and only fifty percent for the
remaining eight years.
</P>
<P>
"The key to becoming a wealthy merchant is to have a shrewd
brain," he says, "I often ponder customers' demands, write down
their requests, and get more information about antiques from the
Internet, TV programs, and newspapers."
</P>
<P>
Since Pingyao was listed as a key world heritage site by UNESCO
in 1997, Mao's shop is always packed with people from all over.
</P>
<P>
Kong Xiangyi, a banking analyst, says that those bankers in
Pingyao had a great deal of prestige a century ago, and that
glorious tradition and pioneering spirit can be carried forward by
later generations.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, more flexible government policies and economic
reforms may just give them the chance to exercise their abilities,
he adds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
