<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Fraud Move Helps Increase Foreign Exchange Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Director of the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE) Wu Xiaoling said today
that the nationwide foreign exchange inspection conducted recently
will help increase China's foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
"The figure of foreign exchange reserves to be released for
September will surely be bigger than that contained in the last
release," she said.
</P>
<P>
The official figure of foreign exchange reserves in early
August was 140.2 billion U.S. dollars, lower than the figure of
140.7 billion U.S. dollars published at the end of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that the latest anti-fraud move has discovered several
billions of U.S. dollars in fake customs reports.
</P>
<P>
She said that there are a number of reasons for the stagnancy
of the country's foreign exchange reserves: delayed payment by
trade partners in some Asian countries hit by the financial
crisis; the raising of the quota of foreign exchange for
individual applications; residents prefer to deposit in foreign
exchange after interest cuts of Renminbi; and foreign exchange
fraud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
