<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Set for Transformation: Kenyan Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for East
and South Africa (COMESA) clearing house is set to be transformed
into a Regional Export Services Agency (RESA) to explore the
regional "enormous" potential, said a Kenyan minister.
</P>
<P>
Minister for East African and Regional Cooperation Nicholas
Biwott said Monday that if the body's Clearing House is well
restructured, 100,000 new job opportunities will be created in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the trade volume in the region would also go up by
4.8 billion Shillings (800 million U.S. Dollars), he was quoted
by Kenyan press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA Clearing House was formed in 1981 to create a
machinery for the settlement of trade and services payments among
the member countries.
</P>
<P>
The transformation is expected to assist regional business by
expediting transfer of funds to suppliers of goods and services,
and providing for continuing education on trade and business
development issues.
</P>
<P>
In the process, the Clearing House is expected to offer a
service that covers political risk whenever a financial
institution is willing to cover the associated commercial risk.
This will be known as African Guarantee Facility (AGF).
</P>
<P>
The house will also offer the Fast Payment Facility, based on
reciprocal payments and credits agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, the move would generate 177 million Dollars for its
shareholders over the next decade," Biwott said at a one-day
workshop on the introduction of the Fast Payment Facility (FAP),
organized by COMESA.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Tourism Industry Shows Huge Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) said Tuesday that 1997
saw an increase of 42.10 percent in tourism surplus totaling
161.63 billion baht (4.03 billion dollars), compared with the
surplus of 113.743 billion baht (2.84 billion dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
This was the result of the sudden reduction in expenditure by
outgoing Thai travelers, from 105.621 billion baht (2.64 billion
dollars) in 1996 to 59.125 billion baht (1.48 billion dollars) in
1997, a 44.02 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from incoming tourists totaled 220.754 billion baht
(5.52 billion dollars) in 1997, about the same as the 219.364
billion baht (5.48 billion dollars) recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
TAT Governor Seree Wangpaichitr said they were both a clear
indication of the impact of the country's economic crisis but also
the importance of inbound tourism in facilitating the return to
economic normalcy.
</P>
<P>
The TAT reported 75.8 billion baht (1.90 billion dollars) in
overall spending on shopping, a decline of 10.76 percent last
year. It was a clear reflection of the diminishing purchasing
power of once high-spending tourists like the Japanese and
Koreans. The figure showed the impact of the economic crisis on
travel and tourism.
</P>
<P>
As for tourism revenue in the first 7 months of this year, the
TAT reported 151.70 billion baht (3.79 billion dollars), a 19.4
percent increase over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
International arrivals until July were 4,379,210, a 5.4 percent
increase over 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
