<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Records Huge Trade Deficit in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa recorded
an unexpected trade deficit of 2.96 billion Rand (about 500
million U.S. Dollars) in August from 253 million Rand (42 million
Dollars) in July, local reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The surprise widening in the deficit took the cumulative trade
balance for the year to a deficit of 257 million Rand (42.8
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists had predicted a 700-million-Rand
(117-million-Dollar) surplus, based on the weaker Rand boosting
exports and inhibiting imports.
</P>
<P>
However, exports plummeted last month from July, falling to
11.86 billion Rand (1.98 billion Dollars) from 14.11 billion Rand
(2.35 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists said exports were hurt by slack demand in Asia,
particularly for precious metals and gems. Demand from the rest
of Africa for South Africa's manufactured exports, especially
vehicles, also appeared to have weakened.
</P>
<P>
Imports were slightly up, rising to 14.82 billion Rand (2.47
billion Dollars) in August from 14.36 billion Rand (2.39 billion
Dollars) in July. The import bill was distorted by the purchase
of an airplane, which accounted for about one billion Rand (167
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists worried that they would have to revise their
forecasts for the current account deficit for the year, but said
they would wait for another month's figures before taking a more
pessimistic view.
</P>
<P>
One of the positive spin-offs of the weak Rand was expected to
be a small current account deficit of about one percent of gross
domestic product this year. The deficit is a key indicator for
foreign investors, especially for South Africa, as the country
has a low level of foreign exchange reserves and needs foreign
capital to cover the current account deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devaluation Is Not Viable Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Director of the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE), Wu Xiaoling, told a
press conference today that devaluation of the yuan will not be a
choice for China to stimulate exports.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that a country devalues its currency only when there is
a deficit in the international balance of payments and it does not
have sufficient foreign exchange reserves. China does not have
such a problem.
</P>
<P>
She said that devaluation is always a double-edged sword and
that nobody can say just how much it may contribute to exports,
but that it can certainly have a negative impact on people's
confidence in the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
In the case of China, she said, "increasing domestic demand is
the key. A country this big can not rely on devaluation to
stimulate economic growth." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
