<HEADLINE> Mubarak Justifies Egypt's Growing Military Might </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has dismissed Israel's jitters about Egypt's growing
military power, saying that balanced peace should be supported
with power.
</P>
<P>
"Israel wants to monopolize all types of nuclear weapons and
missiles and to deny others the right to procure the same
weapons," said Mubarak in an exclusive interview with the mass
circulation Arabic daily "Al Ahram."
</P>
<P>
It is quite surprising that while the whole world is playing
the deaf at such Israeli attitude, questions erupt whenever "we"
obtain a missile, said Mubarak in the interview, the first
instalment of which was published on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a balance of powers," the president stressed in
the interview given on the occasion marking the 25th anniversary
of the October 6 victory, noting that Israeli allegations about
the growing Egyptian military power is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
He said that at a time when Israel owns all kinds of nuclear,
chemical and biological weapons, its talk about Egypt's growing
military power is either a "pre-emptive attack" to cover up the
missile they have recently experimented or a political lever to
elicit Egypt's pressure on Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis are working toward a deal on a
U.S. proposal on a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank. The peace process have languished for 19 months over
Israel's settlement building and their differences over the
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
On October 6, 1973, the Egyptian army took Israeli forces by
surprise and crossed the Suez Canal, which Israel had held since
capturing Egypt's Sinai peninsula in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptians were later pushed back, but Arab's first and
initial victory erased the shame of the 1967 defeat and allowed
Egypt to move toward peace.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Egypt and Israel have been rather cool despite
that Egypt became the first country in the Middle East region to
sign a peace treaty with the Jewish state in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Wants Erosion Control Law To Be Followed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China is just getting over
the catastrophic floods of this summer as an inspection team of
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress sets off
to check on how China's Soil Erosion Control Law is being enforced.
</P>
<P>
The team will visit the upper reaches of the Yangtze River and
the middle reaches of the Yellow River. Soil erosion on the upper
reaches of Yangtze has been widely blamed for aggravating this
year's floods because of excessive logging.
</P>
<P>
The team heard reports here today on how the law has been
enforced by 12 ministries. Buhe, vice chairman of the Standing
Committee and head of the the inspection team, said at the meeting
that the Soil Erosion Control Law is meant to protect the
environment, reduce the effects of natural disasters, and control
water and soil resources.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the law took effect seven years ago,
government efforts have had a good effect, but, he added, because
of excessive logging, land abuse, and the discharge of waste into
rivers, the ecology of many large rivers has got worse in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
He attributes the catastrophic flooding on the Yangtze,
Nenjiang, and Songhua rivers this summer to severe soil erosion on
the upper reaches. He says he expects the inspection work to
increase awareness of the need for water and soil conservation and
law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
The people's congresses of Liaoning, Zhejiang, Fujian, Guizhou,
Yunnan, and Qinghai provinces and the Guangxi and Ningxia
autonomous regions and Chongqing municipality have been authorized
to look into the law enforcement situation in regions under their
jurisdiction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
