<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Companies Permitted to Buy, Sell Currency in Other Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to allow
foreign-funded banks to buy and transfer foreign currencies in cities
other than their locations.
</P>
<P>
Wu Xiaoling, director of the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange (SAFE), told a press conference here today that China has
prohibited Chinese banks to handle such business in order to stamp
out fraud.
</P>
<P>
She said that many people used counterfeit documents to
repeatedly purchase foreign currencies from a bank's branches that
are located in different cities.
</P>
<P>
She said that this illegal activity is hard to monitor at
present.
</P>
<P>
However, she said that China will allow foreign banks to
continue to buy and transfer foreign currencies for foreign-funded
enterprises that have already opened settlement accounts with the
banks' branches in different cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
She said that this is aimed to provide convenience for and
retain the business traditions of foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, she said that these foreign-funded enterprises must
apply for registration forms from SAFE.
</P>
<P>
She said that China will intensify supervision on foreign banks
handling sales and transfer of foreign currencies in different
cities.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises have to present the registration
forms when buying or selling foreign currencies in cities
other than their locations. SAFE branches in different cities will
verify the authenticity of the registration forms by calling their
counterpart that issued them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
