<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Industrial Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- China has had an average
industrial growth rate of 12 percent annually over the past twenty
years thanks to the reforms and opening-up policy, according to
the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
In 1997, total industrial assets were worth 11.6 trillion yuan,
26.6 times the 1978 figure, and the added value of the industrial
sector as a whole reached 3.2 trillion yuan, 7.6 times the 1978
figure.
</P>
<P>
The SSB figures also show substantial increases in steel,
cement and chemical fertilizer output.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has also had rapid growth and has played an
important role in industrial development. Last year, 76.5 percent
of the added industrial value came from this sector.
</P>
<P>
The SSB attributes the progress to government policies of
greater managerial authority for industrial enterprises and to the
introduction of foreign funds and advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
The government has also established a modern enterprise
system. More than 2,000 manufacturers had been either closed down
or declared bankrupt by the end of 1997. Nearly 5,000 enterprises
had been purchased or merged.
</P>
<P>
A number of large industrial groups have been formed to give
full scope to the efficiency of operation of scale and advance the
adjustment of the industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
There are, however, some problems, like the large number of
money losers, low economic returns and duplicated construction
projects. The SSB says that more effective measures to deal with
the irrational industrial mix and discrepancies in regional
economic development are needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
