<HEADLINE> Israeli Arabs Strike Over Umm Al-Fahem Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Arabs started a
one-day nationwide strike Tuesday following the two-day clashes
between Israeli Arabs and the Israeli police in Umm Al-Fahem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli security forces have been put on full alert
to prevent further violence during the strike.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian political leaders also called on the
Palestinians in the self-ruled West Bank and Gaza Strip to join
the strike and show their support for the Israeli Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The strike was called for by Israeli Arab leaders to protest
what they described as brutal behavior by Israeli police and
border police during the clashes in Umm Al-Fahem, in which over
100 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
The clashes erupted Sunday after the demolition of a protest
tent set up three weeks ago by the local residents on disputed
land near Umm Al-Fahem, about 30 kilometers southeast of Haifa.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army said that the area is the army's firing
range. The army also said that an agreement was reached with the
residents to nationalize about 50 hectares of their land in
exchange for about six times as much land elsewhere. But local
residents said the land confiscation is unfair.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman expressed his dismay on Monday about
the incidents in Umm Al-Fahem, saying it is important to have
peaceful coexistence between Israeli Arabs and Jewish citizens.
</P>
<P>
"We have to learn to live with the Arab population in this
country," he told the Israel Radio, adding that "it is a shame
there was such a flare-up. Whoever has managed to negotiate a
ceasefire deserves credit."
</P>
<P>
Weizman is scheduled to visit Umm Al-Fahen area Tuesday and
try to settle the dispute, his office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
