<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Urged to Be Realistic in Addressing Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) has been urged to be realistic in
addressing the issue of regional economic crisis instead of
focusing on its long-term vision on what an ideal economy should
be.
</P>
<P>
Making the appeal at the two-day fourth APEC Investment
symposium which began here Tuesday, Malaysian International Trade
and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz said, "Every year during APEC
meeting there is a (new) vision; APEC is the most visionary
forum...I hope it may not be a blurred vision."
</P>
<P>
But if the short-term problems were not addressed properly at
present, they could actually affect the APEC economies in the
long-term as a result, she said while acknowledging that in the
long-term, most members may favor a "perfect" business
environment where trade liberalization is considered as the
ultimate level of achievement.
</P>
<P>
She said that even nations which were not directly involved in
the financial crisis could be indirectly affected due to the
"boomerang" effect if there were no related measures taken at APEC
or other international level.
</P>
<P>
She said every APEC member has the sovereign right to maintain
particular domestic policies based on determined priorities and
objectives because there cannot be one APEC investment regime or
one single APEC framework that can be made applicable across the
board in the region, although some basic investment principles
could be subscribed to by each member economy.
</P>
<P>
It is important that due cognizance be given to the differing
levels of socio-economic development among APEC members which have
made it necessary to implement certain domestic policies to
achieve specific socio-economic activities, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said, "The principle of voluntarism also meant an APEC
economy which cannot subscribe to any particular investment
principle should not be regarded as less favored as a host
location for investors."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that in trade liberalization, APEC has "high
ideals" of achieving barrier-free trade and barrier-free
investment environments within the region, with impeded cross-flow
of investments being guaranteed via most favored nation or
treatment status.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, these are noble objectives, but as in anything else
in the real economic environment, such high ideals must
necessarily be tempered by pragmatism and reality," she said.
</P>
<P>
APEC comprises Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong
Kong (China), Indonesia, Japan, Mexico, Malaysia, New Zealand,
Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, Chinese
Taipei, Thailand and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium is hosted by the Malaysian Industrial
Development Authority (MIDA) on behalf of the APEC Investment
Experts Group (IEG). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0204 </DOCNO>
