<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Masses at Congo (K) Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan troops have deployed
heavily and have been put on alert along the frontline bordering
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) following reported
bombings of a Ugandan village by DRC war planes Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of the Bukaka Village in western district of
Bundibugyo was the second in about two months. The first was in
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
A New Vision report said Tuesday that commanders of Ugandan
People's Defense Forces could not be reached for the confirmation
of the size of the fresh deployment, but quoted unnamed senior
officers as saying that they have the manpower to guard the
country from any foreign aggression.
</P>
<P>
A team of experts was dispatched to assess the damage from the
bombing, it added.
</P>
<P>
The local paper noted it was still too early to say the
bombing was in retaliation to Uganda's alleged involvement in the
eight-week-long armed conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Banyamulenge soldiers rose against DRC
President Laurent Kabila on August 2, Kabila has directed his
finger of blame at Uganda, souring relations between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a BBC report said that Sudan declared a state of
general mobilization Monday to confront what it called an attack
by Uganda and Eritrea in the southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the Sudanese government declared a
nationwide mobilization since January 1997 when Khartoum said it
had been invaded by Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Sudan accuses Eritrea, Uganda and Ethiopia of fighting with
the Sudan People's Liberation Army. All the three countries deny
the allegations.  
</P>
