<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say Yangtze River Can Clean Itself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Yangtze River, which
runs through China's several nonferrous-metal-rich areas, has not
suffered any metal pollution, and scientists recently discovered
that the river can clean itself up.
</P>
<P>
Metal pollution accidents have been reported on tributaries
along the lower reaches of the Yangtze in Hunan, Jiangxi and Anhui
provinces, which are rich in cadmium, mercury, lead and zinc
deposits. The stibium deposits in Hunan account for 48 percent of
the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have studied Hunan's Dongting Lake, China's second
largest and a major fish and rice producer, and found that
tributaries running into the lake bring in pollutants like
cadmium, stibium, mercury and lead. But after mixing with the
Yangtze River water, the poisonous elements disappear.
</P>
<P>
They explain that when the Yangtze passes through the Three
Gorges area, its calcium and magnesium content rises greatly and
the water is alkaline. The alkaline water then neutralizes the
acid water from the tributaries in the lake.
</P>
<P>
Chemical compounds from the neutralization process have been
found in soil layers around the lake and, scientists say, are
buried in the soil, controlling the spread of pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say the river's ability to clean itself is the
reason for its good natural environment and why it has become
China's major rice and fish production base, as well as one of the
origins of Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
However, they also warn that human's abuse of the river and
industrial pollution will damage the river's ability to clean
itself and that pollution must be controlled before it is too
late.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0208 </DOCNO>
