<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Verification on Current Account Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
revealed today that a recent nation-wide foreign exchange
inspection has discovered fake customs reports involving several
billions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference today, Director of the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE) Wu Xiaoling said that
ever since the beginning of this year, the number of foreign
exchange defraud and tax rebate swindling cases with fake
documents have been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
To deal with this situation, SAFE and some other related
government organizations jointly launched a foreign exchange
inspection in July to verify the reality of all the customs
reports valued above 200,000 U.S. dollars under foreign exchange
purchase and payment by TT, LC and D/P in the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Based on the findings of this inspection, SAFE has enhanced
verifications for current account transactions, in a bid to
safeguard the national economic security, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
She said that, to provide convenience for enterprises' buying
and transferring of foreign exchange and improve the speed and
efficiency of verification, SAFE, the customs and banks are
working closely to build a computer data communication network.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the aim of enhancing verification for current
account exchange is to prevent capital transfer in the name of
current account transactions.
</P>
<P>
"Enterprises' demand for foreign exchange for current account
transactions and individuals' demand for foreign exchange for
private purposes shall be satisfied upon the presentation of
necessary documents to banks," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
