<HEADLINE> Philippines to End Deal With Cathay Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- With Philippine Airlines (PAL)
expected to resume operations next week, the Philippine government
is to end the lease agreement with Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific
Airways, allowing the airline's temporary takeover of the domestic
routes left by PAL.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said here Tuesday that he
has already received orders from President Joseph Estrada to
inform Cathay Pacific of the deal's termination.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has succeeded in brokering an agreement between the PAL
management and PAL labor union that will lead to PAL's likely
re-opening on October 7.
</P>
<P>
Labor union officials informed the president Monday that they
have decided to accept the offer of PAL chairman Lucio Tan for
employees to accept a suspension of their collective bargaining
agreement for 10 years in exchange for a 20 percent ownership of
the airline and three seats in the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific and a subsidiary of the Philippine National Bank
signed Sunday a lease agreement allowing the Hong Kong-based
airline to fill the void left by PAL's closure on September 23.
</P>
<P>
Starting Monday, Cathay Pacific aircraft began flying major
domestic routes in the Philippines under the lease agreement.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Executive Secretary Zamora also said that the
government is eyeing the sale of its shares in PAL to investors
who want to infuse capital into the airline. 
</P>
