<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Govt Out to Deal With Serious Economic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley launched here Tuesday the NZ Government's "Policies
for Progress" to deal with the shrinking economy and worsening
financial situation.
</P>
<P>
According to the scheme, which is contained in Shipley's
statement, the New Zealand Government will sell state-owned
Contact Energy, postpone the deadline for removing all tariffs,
and move the floor for superannuation from 65 percent of the
average wage to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said in the statement that the government has agreed to
work towards the sale of Contact Energy. Money from the sale will
"help us back into surplus and pay off debt".
</P>
<P>
According to Treasurer Bill Birch, the Contact Energy has a
book value of 860 million NZ dollars (430 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The NZ government rejected the suggestion of removing all
tariffs immediately in 2000 and has reached agreement on a
timeline for the reduction of tariffs to zero in 2006, Shipley
said.
</P>
<P>
"This track also sees New Zealand meet its international
obligations in good time," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to Shipley, the lowering of the floor for
superannuation "will help to ensure the affordability and
sustainability of the current scheme".
</P>
<P>
She noted the "Policies for Progress" see "us managing our
budget so we can invest in our future while still acting
responsibly in relation to international economic realities".
</P>
<P>
The new measures will go through the Parliament in the next
three days, Shipley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
