<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Ban On Cutting Natural Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 loggers in
the city of Chongqing have started planting and protecting trees
instead of cutting them as part of a Chinese government project to
protect natural forest resources.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing no longer allows local people to cut down a single
tree. Specialists say that the ecology in the city, which sprawls
along the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, has a very important
bearing on the safety of the Three Gorges Reservoir and the
safety, lives, and property of people living along the middle and
lower reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Excessive cutting and uncontrolled farming have reduced the
forest coverage in the city to 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
A local forestry bureau official says that Chongqing now has
only about 1.14 million hectares of natural forests and he
stresses the significance of protecting natural forests because of
their contribution to soil and water conservation, and climatic
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has allocated 100 million yuan (12 million
U.S. dollars) to help Chongqing re-employ loggers and people who
work in the forest industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
