<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Securities Bill Tabled in Malaysian Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Securities
Industries (Central Depository) (Amendment) Bill 1998 was tabled
Tuesday in Parliament, which aims at ensuring transparency in
security transactions in an effort to restore investor confidence
in Malaysia's stock market.
</P>
<P>
The bill was tabled by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad, who is also first finance minister, at the House of
Representatives which began a two-day special sitting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed amendments cover 28 clauses, including new
definitions, ruling against security withdrawals, mandatory
deposits for fixed securities and ruling against off-market
transactions.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir explained the rationale for the amendments and said
the proposed amendments are necessary to reinforce administrative
measures taken by the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE), the
Securities Clearing Automated Network Services (SCANS) and the
Malaysian Central Depository (MCD).
</P>
<P>
He said the move was in line with the National Economic
Recovery Plan, It was also in keeping with the need to restore
investor confidence in the market and as such administrative and
legal measures would have to be taken immediately.
</P>
<P>
The amendments aimed at enhancing transparency and transactions
of KLSE-listed shares and confine dealings to only at the KLSE or
other legally recognized stock markets, thus banning off-market
transactions like the Central Limit Order Book (CLOB).
</P>
<P>
The amendments also seek to check misuse of nominees by
requiring all equity holdings be made in the name of the
beneficial owner or authorized nominee.
</P>
<P>
The amendments would also provide for penalties to be imposed
on those contravening the rules and regulations governing
securities trading in Malaysia or trading involving shares of
Malaysian companies.
</P>
<P>
The bill would also beef up enforcement capabilities of
regulatory agencies to ensure prompt and effective actions
against violators of the securities procedures and rulings,
Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis has exposed various weaknesses in the
securities industry which required to be rectified in order to
restore confidence in the Malaysian capital market, Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Parliament will debate at the special sitting several bills
relating to the securities industry, futures trading and
companies.
</P>
<P>
Other bills to be debated include the Securities Industry
(Amendment) Bill 1998, Futures Trading Industry (Amendment) Bill
1998, Securities Commission (Amendment) Bill 1998 and Companies
(Amendment) (No.2) Bill 1998.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives will sit for two days starting
Tuesday while the Senate will sit Wednesday and Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0222 </DOCNO>
