<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Turkish newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom)
</P>
<P>
-- Senior police officers from 11 countries including Germany,
the Netherlands and Belgium gathered Monday in Istanbul, the
largest city in Turkey, to discuss measures of fighting smuggling
and organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long been used as a springboard for drug
trafficking and other transnational crimes because of its
geographical position linking Asia to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Sabah (Morning)
</P>
<P>
-- The Austrian Embassy in Ankara, on behalf of the European
Union (EU), issued a statement Monday expressing concern over a
higher Turkish court's approval of a 10-month sentence for
Istanbul Mayor Tayyip Erdogan.
</P>
<P>
"The EU is worried about this decision, which has an influence
on democracy and principles of freedom of expression," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Erdogan was found guilty by the State Security Court in
Diyarbakir, southeast Turkey, in April "for inciting hatred based
on religious differences" in a speech at a political rally.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National)
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey and Mexico signed Monday three agreements aimed at
further expanding economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz said that Turkey would make efforts to enhance its ties
with Mexico and other Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz arrived in the Mexico City Sunday for an official visit
to Mexico from New York where he attended the U.N. General
Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
