<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM Meets CPC Top Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley here Tuesday morning met with Wei Jianxing, member
of the Political Bureau Standing Committee of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), who was paying an
official good-will visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
Shipley and Wei had a cordial and friendly conversation on
Sino-New Zealand relations, the situation in Asia and other issues
of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Wei, who also is a member of the Secretariat of the CPC Central
 Committee, praised Prime Minister Shipley for her consistently
adhering to her country's "one China" policy and her efforts to
promote New Zealand's friendly relations of cooperation with China
since she took office.
</P>
<P>
He said that in recent years China and New Zealand have seen
their friendly exchanges growing and mutually beneficial
cooperation expanded. Frequent contacts and exchange of visits
between leaders of the two countries in particular have played an
extremely important role in increasing mutual understanding,
expanding common grounds, strengthening cooperation and developing
friendship, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wei noted that both China and New Zealand are Asian-Pacific
countries and share many interests and responsibilities. As the
new century is approaching, China desires to strengthen and
develop its friendly relations with New Zealand, and work together
with it and other peace-loving countries to make new contribution
to safeguarding and promoting peace, stability and development in
the region and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Shipley lauded China for its important contribution to
stabilizing the Asian economy by maintaining sustained economic
growth and the value of its currency at a time when Asia is facing
a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
She said her country is satisfied with the steadily-growing New
Zealand-China friendship and cooperation. New Zealand has adhered
to and will continue to adhere to its "one China" policy, she
said.
</P>
<P>
She pledged continued efforts to promote mutually-beneficial
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday morning, Wei Jianxing also met with New Zealand
Minister for International Trade Lockwood Smith. They exchanged
views on furthering economic and trade links between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday afternoon, Wei left Wellington for Australia after
concluding his visit to New Zealand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
