<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mid-Year Gems Emporium to Be Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A mid-year gems emporium will
be held here from October 16 to 22 and preparations are underway,
according to the Myanmar mines authorities.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 gems merchants from 20 countries and regions, mostly
from Japan, Thailand, China and China's Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, are expected to attend the emporium, the
seventh of its kind.
</P>
<P>
At the emporium, gems, jade, pearl and jewelry will be sold at
competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, a well-known producer of jade, ruby and sapphire in
the world, has held gems emporiums annually since 1964 with
additional mid-year ones introduced in the past six years since
1992.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar earned more than 260 million U.S. dollars from the last
35 annual and six mid-year gems emporiums.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar promulgated a new gemstone law in September 1995,
allowing local entrepreneurs to mine, produce, transport and sell
finished gemstone and manufacture jewelry at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
In addition to allowing the local private sector to mine and
process gems in the country, the government also set up
joint-ventures with companies from Thailand and Malaysia for the
activities.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, an Israeli company and a Myanmar private
one jointly set up a gems center here, applying advanced Israeli
methods to produce quality jewelry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
