<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Faces Challenges from Changes in Trade Era: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The garment sector, the major
foreign exchange earner of Bangladesh, will never grow if it
continues to depend on the preferential treatment for export, The
Financial Express daily reported Tuesday, quoting a minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"We must depend on high quality production," Commerce and
Industries Minister Tofael Ahmed said while addressing a seminar
on "Consequence of the GATT (General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade) Uruguay Round for the Textile and Garments Sector in
Bangladesh" held here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will have to develop backward linkage industries for
the ready-made garments sector to retain its market after
elimination of preferential access to the world market in 2005, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The trade regime after the year 2005 will be an opportunity as
well as a challenge for Bangladesh's garment sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ready-made garment sector is the number one foreign
exchange earner of this South Asian country, and it grows at an
average annual rate of over 20 percent. Exports from ready-made
garments stood at 2.845 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 55.09
percent of the total export earnings of 5.16 billion dollars in
the previous fiscal year ending on June 30, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
