<HEADLINE> Moldova Seeks to Enhance Cooperation With NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Moldovan President Petru
Lucinschi said Monday that further cooperation between Moldova and
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) would help stability
and security in Moldova and the whole region.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Kishinev, capital of Moldova, after a
meeting with visiting NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana
Madariaga, the president said that as an active member of NATO's
Partnership for Peace Program(PFP), Moldova would continue to work
to strengthen cooperation with NATO, according to Moldovan
state-run television.
</P>
<P>
The development of ties between Moldova and NATO would not
change the country's neutral status, Lucinschi stressed.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Solana said his visit aimed at fostering ties
between NATO and the former Soviet republic and expressed
satisfaction with their present cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He believed the development of ties would provide a possibility
for peaceful settlement of the regional confrontation and
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Solana also praised Moldova for its active role in
strengthening the pan-European security.
</P>
<P>
Moldova is the first stop of Solana's trip to the republics of
former Soviet Union. He will leave Kishinev on Tuesday for Georgia
and then Azerbaijan and Armenia.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO launched its PFP program in 1994 to help
foster ties with its former Warsaw Pact adversaries and other
neutral countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
