<HEADLINE> Former Malaysian Deputy PM Brought to Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Former Malaysian Deputy
Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim was brought to
the Jalan Raja court complex here Tuesday morning after nine days
in police custody.
</P>
<P>
Anwar will be charged in court on five counts of corruption and
five counts of unnatural sex acts, the Attorney-General's Chambers
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nine of the charges will be mentioned at the court here Tuesday
and one more at the Petaling Jaya court near here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement signed by Special Officer to the
Attorney- General, Shamsuddin Hassan, the Attorney-General as the
public prosecutor was satisfied that there was sufficient "prima
facie" evidence to charge Anwar for the offenses.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, the public prosecutor had decided to charge
Anwar in court on September 22.
</P>
<P>
However, as Anwar was detained under the Internal Security Act
on September 20, the public prosecutor deferred mention of the
case until the security situation returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Attorney-General's Chambers had
scrutinized all the latest statements gathered during police
investigations of Anwar following a report lodged at the Dang
Wangi police station here last June 19.
</P>
<P>
The report was in connection with the book "50 Dalil Mengapa
Anwar Tidak Boleh Jadi PM" (50 reasons why Anwar cannot become
PM).
</P>
<P>
"The Attorney-General's Chambers wish to state here that the
decision to charge Anwar is based only on evidence produced by the
police," according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was sacked from his cabinet posts on September 2,
was arrested by police under the Internal Security Act on
September 20 after calling an illegal assembly here which resulted
in riots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
