<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Heavy Equipment Manufacturer Builds New Base in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.'s Caterpillar
recently started construction work on a branch in the Tianjin
Bonded Zone that is being built with two Japanese companies at a
cost of 47.65 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Duane Devore, a representative of the joint venture, says that
massive construction projects in China provide an opportunity for
foreign engineering machinery manufacturers and that this will be
Caterpillar's headquarters for North Asia.
</P>
<P>
The move will help them cut production costs and make
their products more competitive on the world market, he says,
explaining that Tianjin is an ideal place because its harbour
serves much of China and it is in the center of three
heavily-populated countries: China, Japan and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He says that the joint venture will put 26.49 million
U.S. dollars into a forging factory with a workshop and office
building with 43,000 sq.m. of floor space. Caterpillar is also
negotiating with the Chinese to build an engine plant.
</P>
<P>
Caterpillar has spent one billion yuan already on two
Sino-American joint ventures: an engineering machinery plant in
Jiangsu Province and a forging plant in Shanxi Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
