<HEADLINE> Rapid Tourism Expansion in Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Southwestern China has the
greatest potential for tourism development in China in the new
millennium, according to Sun Gang, deputy director of the China
National Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
Southwestern China refers to Sichuan, Yunnan, and Guizhou
provinces, the Tibet and Guangxi Zhuang autonomous regions, and
the city of Chongqing. It has 35 of the country's 120 major
state-level scenic sites.
</P>
<P>
The region has most of China's ethnic groups and diverse
architecture, unique folklore and local customs, and picturesque
mountains and landscapes.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the region had 2.42 million overseas tourists and
earned more than one billion U.S. dollars from tourism, up 19.3
and 40.5 percent over the previous year, respectively. Meanwhile
nearly 127 million domestic tourists visited, contributing 25.2
billion yuan in earnings.
</P>
<P>
However, it accounts for less than eight percent of China's
tourism, and a greater effort needs to be made to develop tourist
sector in the region, Sun told a recent tourism promotion
conference in Guiyang, capital of Guizhou.
</P>
<P>
An effort has been made to improve the tourist infrastructure,
airports, tourist hotels, and restaurants. And there are 170
domestic and overseas air routes connecting the region with the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
At the conference attended by tourism authorities from the
provinces, lists of carefully selected tourist programs were
presented.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
