<HEADLINE> Motorcycle World Champion Set to Quit after Next Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Australia's four-time 500cc
motorcycle racing world champion Mick Doohan Tuesday said in
Sydney he would likely quit after next season.
</P>
<P>
Doohan said that "I've decided to continue again for next year
but I doubt I'll go for 2000. I think new century, new job."
</P>
<P>
Doohan noted that he would like to top Italian Giacomo
Agostini's long standing victory record.
</P>
<P>
Agostini won 68 500cc races between 1965 and 1976, and won the
championship eight times between 1966 and 1975.
</P>
<P>
Monaco-based Doohan expects to remain living in Europe, rather
than returning home to Australia. "Everything's so familiar to me
over there," Doohan said.
</P>
<P>
There are just two rounds of competition remaining in the
world championship -- the Australian GP on October 4 and in
Buenos Aires, Argentina on October 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
