<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lands To Be Returned to Dongting Lake in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A large part of Dongting
Lake in central China's Hunan Province has been turned into
farmland over the past few decades, but now the provincial
government plans to stop the practice and return the cultivated
land to the lake.
</P>
<P>
The consistent degeneration of wetlands as a result of
excessive reclamation has been widely regarded by local experts as
a major cause of this summer's devastating flooding along the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The lake covered 4,400 sq. km. in 1949, but in the following
decades it suffered a loss of more than one third of its area from
repeated enclosures of wetlands for cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The shrinking of the lake's water storage capacity has caused
increasingly frequent floods, especially in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has spent a total of four billion
yuan in constructing dikes around the lake in the past four
decades, but has reaped few benefits. This summer's flood caused a
loss of 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to a provincial program, Hunan will return a total of
1,260 sq.km. of farmland to Dongting Lake in the coming five
years, involving the relocation of some 1.2 million people, in a
bid to bring the lake back to its 1994 size.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the ambitious program remain unknown, but
China's central government has earmarked special fund estimated
at over 25 billion yuan for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Recently, local people have increased their calls for greater
care for the increasingly-worsening environment in the lake area,
due to decades of urbanization and industrialization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferrochrome Base Under Construction in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- A new ferrochrome production
base, the largest of its kind in China, is currently under
construction on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
The mine in Lopusa, a word meaning treasured land in Tibetan,
sits at 4,100 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
The Lopusa Ferrochrome Mining Area offers the largest proven
ferrochrome deposits in China. The area will include two major
mines -- the Mount Jamka and Lopusa mines.
</P>
<P>
The Lopusa mine, operated by the Tibet Mining Joint Stock
Company, will have an annual production capacity of 120,000
tons. Ore produced will have a ferrochrome content of 50 percent
and above.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 86.5 million yuan for construction
of the Lopusa Mine, with an additional 25.4 million yuan earmarked
for the Mount Jamka Mine in during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Ferrochrome is widely used by the machine-building, chemical
and leather processing industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
