<HEADLINE> Modernizing China's Golog Grasslands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Dawu, capital of the Golog
Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture in China's Qinghai Province has
taken on a new look with its wide roads, power grids, and
telephone lines in recent years.
</P>
<P>
No one ever thought that Dawu would have telephone booths along
its streets or electric appliances in the homes of the prefecture
on the 70,000-square-kilometers of grassland in what was one of
the province's most underdeveloped areas.
</P>
<P>
But, in 1994, the local government spent 100 million yuan
(about 12 million U.S. dollars) on a 110-kv power grid that now
allows local people to use such conveniences as televisions,
refrigerators, and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
A 500-kilometer optical fiber cable was run from Xining,
Qinghai's capital, to Golog last June, at a cost of 30 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The head of the local telecommunications bureau said that 60
percent of Dawu's families now have telephones and that some
herdsmen even have pagers and mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
The latest and largest construction project in the prefecture
is the 400-km Ningguo Highway, which shortens the distance from
Xining to Golog by some 300 km. and trucks have begun to bring in
fresh vegetables and rice from southern China and variety to local
markets, so that the once desolate grasslands are beginning to
prosper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Italy Urge Belgrade to Comply with UN on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen and his Italian counterpart Beniamino Andreatta Monday
stressed the need to deal firmly with Yugoslavian President
Slobodan Milosevic on the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting of the two in Rome, Cohen warned that the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) could use air strikes against
Serb targets if Milosevic failed to comply with the United Nations
resolution calling for an immediate end to the violence in the
Serbian province and the resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, where 90 percent of the population is ethnic Albanian,
has been torn by bloody conflict since earlier this year between
government forces and ethnic separatists fighting for independence.
</P>
<P>
"On the basis of past experience, we know that Milosevic won't
be convinced by weak threats. We must therefore be strong, so
that he finally decides to pull his military forces out and allow
humanitarian aid into Kosovo," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to bring him to the negotiating table where we can
peacefully negotiate a resolution for this situation."
</P>
<P>
Cohen stressed that, with winter coming, some 50,000 people who
fled the violence to nearby mountains might die of hunger and cold.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta, for his part, said he and Cohen had spoken of "the
necessary military pressure which might be required" if Belgrade
failed to comply with the UN resolution.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that Milosevic, even at the last minute, realizes how
isolated he is from the rest of the world, as well as NATO's
determination to use all means in defense of humanitarian aims,"
Andreatta said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Italian government would assess its
commitment to possible military action over the next few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
