<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province to Accelerate Marine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 29 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
recently worked out an ambitious plan which will turn the marine
industry into a pillar of its economy.
</P>
<P>
Shandong expects the marine industry to yield an added value of
180 billion yuan by the year 2010, equivalent to 10 percent to its
expected gross domestic product (GDP) in that year.
</P>
<P>
To meet this goal, the province will optimize its marine
structure and give priority to exploitation of offshore petroleum
and the development of marine pharmaceutical production, refined
chemicals, tourism and comprehensive utilization of seawater.
</P>
<P>
Bordering the Bohai and Yellow seas, Shandong has a
3,100-kilometer-long coastline, one-sixth of China's total.
</P>
<P>
The province began to tap marine resources in 1991 and since
then has led the country in sea aquaculture, chemical salt
production and offshore petroleum development.
</P>
<P>
Shandong's annual marine output value grew by 17 percent in
each of the past seven years and soared to 36.6 billion yuan last
year, accounting for 5.5 percent of the province's GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
