<HEADLINE> Urbanization In Northeastern Chinese County </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Haicheng, a prosperous
county in northeast China's Liaoning Province, has been urbanizing
by adding hotels, restaurants, gyms, and swimming pools in the
county seat.
</P>
<P>
It also has Xiliu Market, a popular garment marketplace that
did 15 billion yuan in business last year.
</P>
<P>
Haicheng County, which covers 2,700 sq. km. and has a
population of 1.08 million, was selected by China's Construction
Ministry out of 2,000-odd counties as a pilot in the urbanization
drive and 3.15 billion yuan has been spent on urban construction
since the early 1990s, improving infrastructure a great deal.
</P>
<P>
Tap water is now available in 50 percent of the county's rural
areas and 70 percent of the county's roads are hard surface.
</P>
<P>
Computerized telephone service is now available in 27 villages
and towns.
</P>
<P>
The county had a GDP of 16 billion yuan and 480 million yuan in
revenues last year. Per capita income of farmers was 3,641 yuan in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The city of Dalian is to the south, Anshan is to the north, the
Liaohe Oilfield to the west, and the coal-rich city of Fushun and
iron-rich city of Benxi to the east. It has abundant talcum and
magnesite reserves and produces fruits, vegetables, rice, and corn.
</P>
<P>
Urbanization development programs in Haicheng were listed as
Sino-Japanese technological cooperation projects at the 17th
annual Sino-Japanese government meeting in Tokyo in May of 1997. A
delegation representing the Japanese International Cooperation
Agency made a fact-finding tour to Haicheng in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
