<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Business Growth in Southern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Private businesses have been
making greater contributions to the economic growth of China's
Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
Hainan had 111,000 self-employed small businesses by the end of
June, 48 percent more than in 1988, when the province was set
up. They provide jobs to about 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The number of private enterprises this year came to 15,000 and
that of employees more than 100,000, which are 39 times and 20
times the 1988 level respectively.
</P>
<P>
These private businesses paid 876 million yuan in taxes in
1997, accounting for 28 percent of the province's total amount.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the businesses accounted for 23
percent of the province's taxes, or 360 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
There is a growing number of large private enterprises each
with annual business turnover exceeding 100 million yuan. Many
private businesses are expanding by mergering, issuing shares and
through joint efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
