<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changing Face Of Shanghai's Harbor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shanghai
announced at a recent conference on developing Huangpu Harbor area
that it will turn the harbor area in the downtown area into a
multi-purpose commercial center as part of the international
metropolis.
</P>
<P>
The city will move all coal, chemical, and bulk cargo docks in
a 2-million-sq.m. area along the Huangpu River to a new port area
on the outskirts of Shanghai and use the site for a modern urban
commerce, tourist, and recreation center within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai port was built in 1843 and is now China's
largest. But, as it expanded into the outskirts in recent years,
wharfs in the urban began to decline in cargo handling and had a
negative effect on the urban environment.
</P>
<P>
The wharf relocating began last year and a coal dock halted
operations early this year, and the Dada Passenger Wharf has
already become a business street.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Port Office and the Koos Real Estate Development Group
Regal (Overseas) Assets Ltd. recently set up a joint venture, the
Shanghai P &AMP; K Development Co., to manage the transformation
scheme and the U.S. Skidmore Owings &AMP; Merrill International
Ltd. is responsible for the overall design of the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
