<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves 1999 Defense Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congress on Monday
approved a 1999 defense budget bill totalling 250.5 billion
U.S. dollars which would enable the Pentagon to finance its
anti-missile defenses and a pay raise for military personnel.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers, after a short debate, approved by a vote of 369
to 43 the defense measure. A 21.3-billion-dollar energy and water
bill for the new fiscal year was also passed by 389 to 25 votes.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is expected to approve both measures in the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
The defense bill, which accounts for about 15 percent of total
federal spending next year, includes 70.6 billion dollars for
military personnel, 84 billion dollars for operations and
maintenance and 48.5 billion dollars for purchasing new weapons
and equipment.
</P>
<P>
It represents a 2.8-billion-dollar increase over the current
level, but President Bill Clinton and many lawmakers of both
parties say it is insufficient. They are working on a separate
bill that would include 1.9 billion dollars for U.S. peacekeeping
troops in Bosnia and one billion dollars for training and
intelligence operations.
</P>
<P>
With the personnel spending hike, the services would give the
troops a 3.6 percent pay raise. More than 950 million dollars
will be spent on anti-missile defense research.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, about 500 million dollars will be used to
purchase seven C130 cargo planes and 45 million dollars to
construct a giant LHD-8 transport ship.
</P>
<P>
The energy and water bill includes 1.4 billion dollars for the
construction of more than 200 Army Corps of Engineers water
projects.
</P>
<P>
To balance the accounts, the bill allows for the trimming of
administration requests for the Energy Department's environmental
cleanups and research on solar and other forms of renewable
energy, as well as Tennessee Valley flood control, dam maintenance
and other programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
