<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Amends Land Utilization Management Procedures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 29 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar land utilization
authorities has amended its procedures conferring the right to
cultivate and utilize land for agriculture and livestock breeding
purposes prescribed on December 12, 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to a notification on Monday of the Central Committee
for the Management of Culturable, Fallow and Waste Land,
cultivation of perennial plants will be allowed to extend up to
20,250 hectares from the originally prescribed 2,025 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Organizations involving foreigners, who want to carry out such
extensive undertakings, need not undergo approval from the Foreign
Investment Commission, the notification said.
</P>
<P>
Natural resources above and below the ground shall not be
extracted and if the resources are found in the authorized land,
then the land shall be surrendered to the government if the
government is desirous of undertaking the same, it said.
</P>
<P>
If infrastructures such as roads and railway lines are desired
to be built on the authorized land required by the state, then it
shall also be surrendered to the government, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in the 1997-98 fiscal year
which ended in March, fallow land in Myanmar measured 1.1 million
hectares, culturable waste land 7.89 million hectares and sown
areas under crops 12.51 million hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
