<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shortage Of Funds For Protecting China's Relics (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Some ruins from the late
Shang Dynasty (1300-1050 B.C.) at the Yinxu site in the city of
Anyang in central China's Henan Province, where the earliest known
Chinese characters inscribed on animal bones were unearthed, face
many serious threats, but the major one is the shortage of funds.
</P>
<P>
Many valuable things like foundations of palaces and temples,
tombs, bronzes, jade carvings, and oracle bones have been
unearthed at the site since it was discovered in 1899. Although
the local government has spent nearly 10 million yuan (about 1.2
million U.S. dollars) protecting the Yinxu relics, there are still
problems.
</P>
<P>
An archaeologist with the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
said that excavations at Yinxu over the past 70 years only account
for a third of Yinxu's total area, and there are still immense
quantities of relics buried.
</P>
<P>
Duan Zhenmei, director of the Anyang Yinxu Management Bureau,
said that local people have actually sacrificed a lot in
protecting Yinxu. While farmers in other places become affluent by
developing rural enterprises, farmers in the Yinxu protection zone
suffer from many restrictions on establishing enterprises and
their income is much lower than those outside the protection zone.
</P>
<P>
What is more, farmers have to apply to the relics management
bureau for a permit to build a house and have to pay fees.
</P>
<P>
There are 18 villages with thousands of people. To move these
people out of the protection zone would mean a big problem and at
least 200 million yuan (some 20 million US dollars) just to
relocate two villages, Duan explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Games Organizers Explore Ways of Raising Cash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Sydney Olympic organizers
Tuesday said that they are exploring some new ways of raising
cash for the 2000 Olympic Games, according to reports from
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Organizers want to sell companies the right to put their names
on warm-up events and Games venues in the pre-Olympic year.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG)
president Michael Knight said that "We've never budgeted for
revenue coming in from the test events. We've just had this
fabulous test event on Sydney harbour and we never went to the
market place seeking any revenue to come in from that."
</P>
<P>
Knight noted that the test events are not conducted under
Olympic sponsorship rules.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Olympcis budget was revised to 1.475 billion U.S.
dollars. The cost of staging the Games has increased by 76
million U.S. dollars in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The New South Wales State government has ordered the
organizing committee to put aside any savings in the next two
years to help pay for the swelling costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
