<HEADLINE> Shanghai Seeks Overseas Investment for Pollution Control Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
economic powerhouse, seeks overseas investment for a number of
pollution control projects over the next three years, according to
official sources here.
</P>
<P>
The projects, involving a total investment of more than 400
million U.S. dollars, include pollution control, comprehensive use
of resources, production of environment monitoring instruments,
and energy-saving lamps.
</P>
<P>
The projects constitute part of a municipal plan to readjust
the city's economic structure by developing environment-friendly
industries, said a municipal economic commission official.
</P>
<P>
Some of the funds and key production lines will be imported
from abroad, sources said.
</P>
<P>
An iron-smelting project, which will cost 370 million
U.S. dollars to build, is designed to turn out 800,000 tons of
molten iron annually with advanced waste treatment facilities. It
will help prevent the Pudong Iron and Steel Complex from
discharging pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Another is a fluorescent lamp project which will cost 24
million U.S. dollars in overseas funds to import a production line
and auxiliary equipment to produce 12 million T5 fluorescent lamps
annually.
</P>
<P>
The economic commission will announce more pollution control
projects for overseas investment and cooperation in the near
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
