<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chairman of CONI Resigns over Anti-doping Test Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Mario Pescante, chairman of
Italy's national Olympic Committee (CONI), resigned today
following a scandal over apparently fraudulent anti-doping tests
at the organization's main laboratory.
</P>
<P>
Pescante, who announced his departure as he emerged from a
meeting with CONI's two deputy chairmen, said the decision had
been a collegiate one and was intended to "restore serenity to
the scene."
</P>
<P>
There have been calls from Pescante's resignation ever since
he admitted on September 5 that CONI's anti-doping unit in
Acquacetosa, near Rome, had used extremely hit-and-miss methods
in testing soccer players' urine samples.
</P>
<P>
According to prosecutors in Turin, samples at the Acquacetosa
lab were tested for anabolic steroids only in 20 percent of
cases, for diuretics in only 5-10 percent of cases and never
tested for two illegal growth-enhancing hormones.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the lab issued complete results and last year
was paid four billion lire by CONI for doing so.
</P>
<P>
Pescante's admission came less than two weeks after CONI's
anti-doping panel closed a 14-day investigation with the
announcement that Italian soccer was free from doping.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks later, on September 18, the CONI chief said that he
has forced to admit that the results of anti-doping tests run on
soccer players appeared to be missing from laboratories.
</P>
<P>
Pescante has denied knowing about the haphazard testing
procedures, but admitted to being formally responsible.
</P>
<P>
"I would have preferred to leave the stage on an Olympic
victory chariot, pulled by white horses," Pescante said. "But the
important thing is to have a past that one can look back on with
dignity."
</P>
<P>
He denied that he was abandoning his post because he was
afraid of what would emerge from the commission of enquiry which
Italian Deputy Prime Minister Walter Veltroni ordered to
investigate the scandal earlier this month. The commission will
report on its findings by mid-October.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not resigning because I think I'm guilty of anything,"
Pescante stressed. "I prefer to see it in a positive light and
say I'm doing it to restore calm."
</P>
<P>
Pescante, 60, who won national honors in middle-distance
running as a schoolboy, had been CONI's chairman since June 30,
1993. He was reelected in July 1997 and was to have remained in
the job until after the Sydney Olympic Games of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Last year he failed to achieve a key ambition when Rome's bid
to host the 2004 Olympic Games was beaten by a stronger challenge
from Athens. Before becoming CONI chairman, Pescante spent 20
years as CONI secretary general. He headed the Italian team at
five summer Olympics and five winter ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0280 </DOCNO>
