WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat on Monday began a meeting to break an impasse in the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met
Netanyahu and Arafat in New York preparing for the
summit. (Clinton-Arafat-Netanyahu)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BLACKPOOL, Britain -- British finance minister Gordon Brown
said here on Monday that Britain will not rule out joining the
single currency as its economic interests lied in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Labor Party Conference at this northwestern
coastal city, the Chancellor of the Exchequer said that at a time
when the balance of risks in the world economy is shifting, "a
Britain facing up to the challenges must work with other countries
and implement a reform agenda for global stability and growth."
(UK-Single Currency) 
</P>
