<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreman and Holmes to Fight in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 28 (Xinhua) -- George Foreman and Larry
Holmes, both grandfathers near 50 years old, announced Monday in
Houston that they will have a fight on January 23.
</P>
<P>
The two heavyweight champions of last year are both Americans.
Foreman, fighting in his hometown, will celebrate his 50 years
birthday on January 10, while Holmes turns 49 on November 3.
</P>
<P>
"Usually, the doctors check a fighter's heart, but with Larry
and me, they're just going to see if we have a pulse," Foreman
said.
</P>
<P>
Holmes, (66-6) expects a better fight this time. "This will be
a classic, it's history," he said. "It's two men who over the
decades, never fought. Two men with lots of pride. Two men will
give it all and only one will win. I'm sure that it will be me
and George thinks it will be him."
</P>
<P>
Foreman (76-5) made a comeback from retirement in 1987, and
became the WBA champion in 1994 with a 10th-round knockout of
Michael Moorer.
</P>
<P>
Foreman was champion in 1973-74 before he lost his title to
Muhammad Ali on October 30, 1974. Holmes' championship career
lasted from 1978-1985.
</P>
<P>
"Larry Holmes was a second-rate fighter sparring for Ali when
I had my original career," Foreman said. "This is the only time
this fight could be made. This is the only time it is important.
It's going to be a good fight, a mental matchup."
</P>
<P>
Foreman reportedly will win 10 million U.S. dollars while
Holmes take four million.
</P>
<P>
The combined age of the fighters at 99 is the highest in
boxing history.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care if we're 900 years old," Holmes said. "You got
two old guys almost the same age that are going to fight. We
might not fight like young guys today, but are going to fight."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
