<HEADLINE> Fate of No. 70 Ball Still in Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, Septembe 28 (Xinhua) -- Pil Ozersky caught Mark
McGwire's 70th home-run ball on Sunday, but the 26-year-old
American baseball fan said he is not sure what he'll do with it.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know, because I didn't expect to get this ball," he
said. "Right now I'm excited to see Mr. McGwire and shake his
hand, and that's about as far as I'm looking ahead."
</P>
<P>
McGwire hit his 70th homer to set a fabulous record in his
closing match of the season yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Baseball memorabillia collectors have said they would pay as
much as one million U.S. dollars for the final home-run ball in
McGwire's record run.
</P>
<P>
Ozerskey was in a party room at Busch Stadium with a group of
Washington University research lab scientists and knew he was
lucky to have the ball after diving to come up with the prize.
</P>
<P>
He had a black eye, but he didn't say whether it came from a
struggle for the seventh-inning home run.
</P>
<P>
Kerry Woodson, a body-shop worker, caught No. 69 in the third
inning yesterday. He was hoping against hope it would be the last
one, hence the most valuable ball.
</P>
<P>
Woodson doesn't know what he's going to do with his ball
either, but when McGwire hit No. 70, he said, "Well, it takes the
pressure off me to decide what to do with the ball." 
</P>
</TEXT>
