<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Resolution on U.S. Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council
of the United Nations Monday met on an Arab-sponsored draft
resolution which demanded an immediate U.N. probe into the U.S.
bombing on Sudan's pharmaceutical factory last month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the council ended its meeting, the
council's President Hans Dahlgren of Sweden said he had received a
letter from Lebanese Ambassador Samir Moubrak, the current head of
the informal group of Arab states, known as the Arab Group, with a
copy of the draft resolution in it.
</P>
<P>
"The conclusion of today's meeting is that consultations will
continue among members," Dahlgren said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has accused the El Shifa factory of being
linked with terrorists and producing chemical weapons. But Sudan
says that the factory only produces medicines and veterinary
drugs.
</P>
<P>
Sudan requested an investigation into the U.S. accuses
immediately after the August 20 attack. 
</P>
