<HEADLINE> Least Developed Countries Need World Attention: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Monday appealed to the international community for more
assistance to 48 least developed countries (LDCs) in their efforts
to improve their conditions.
</P>
<P>
"There are three areas in which such help would be particularly
useful: official development assistance (ODA), debt burdens and
market access," he told the annual ministerial meeting of LDCs
held here in the U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he will continue to be "a strenuous advocate" for
reversing the decline of ODA.
</P>
<P>
Turning to trade problems, he said LDCs face high tariffs in
key sectors such as textiles and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Most of the LDCs, with a combined population of close to 600
million, are in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Despite positive growth in their per capita income in the
second half of this decade, the current financial turmoil in
different parts of the world could wipe out the gains made by them
in recent years, Annan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
