<HEADLINE> Arafat Calls on U.N. to Back Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat Monday called on the U.N. General Assembly to
support the establishment of a Palestinian state as a five-year
transitional period ends on May 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
But he stopped short of reaffirming his intention to make a
unilateral declaration of an independent Palestine statehood if a
final peace accord with Israel is not competed by that date.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to call upon all of you, from this place, the
source of international legitimacy and peacekeeping, the guardian
of freedom, security and stability, and the source for the
achievement of justice and prosperity for humankind, to stand by
our people, especially as the five-year transitional period
provided for in the Palestinian-Israeli agreements will end on May
4, 1999 and our people demand of us to shoulder our responsibility
and they await the establishment of their independent state," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"This independent Palestinian state must be established as an
embodiment of their independent people to self-determination," he
said. "I assure you that our people will continue to pursue and
protect the peace of the braves in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
Arafat delivered the speech after returning from Washington,
where he held a last-minute summit with U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on an
Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had previously said that he would use the General
Assembly speech to restate his intention of unilaterally declaring
an independent Palestinian state next year -- even if there is no
final peace agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Arafat has made some concessions, but
the speech he gave Monday appeared to conform with his original
intention.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to you to continue your support for us, as has
always been the case in the decisive moments of the history, the
present and the future of our people," Arafat said. "Help us to
achieve the national goal of our people."
</P>
<P>
Arafat was received with prolonged applause as he was escorted
into the assembly hall by the U.N. chief of protocol. He waved his
right hand and bowed in acknowledgement. U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan sat on the podium when the Palestinian leader was
delivering his speech.
</P>
<P>
It was Arafat's fourth appearance before the assembly since
1974, including a session in Geneva in 1988 when he was denied a
visa to come to New York.
</P>
<P>
However, this was the first time a Palestinian representative
took part in the general debate of the General Assembly -- one of
the fruits of an assembly decision in July to upgrade the status
of the Palestinian U.N. mission, which has U.N. observer status
but is not a full-fledged U.N. member.
</P>
<P>
Arafat noted the occasion in his opening statement, thanking
the assembly for giving the Palestinians the enhanced status
"which we consider to be an essential step towards full
membership."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader was expected to address the morning
session, but his appearance was postponed to allow him to travel
to Washington to meet with Clinton and Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
