<HEADLINE> Council President: It is Legal to Ask Iraq to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- It was legal and
logical for the Security Council of the United Nations to ask Iraq
to cooperate first, Council President said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hans Dahlgren was responding to the remarks made by Iraq's
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz. Aziz said Monday afternoon that
the U.N. Security Council should make the first move towards
ending the latest standoff between Iraq and the United Nations
weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it is both legal and logical to ask Iraq to
cooperate first and then to take the comprehensive review,"
Dahlgren said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan suggested that the Security
Council have more direct engagement with Iraq and conduct a
comprehensive review of Iraq's compliance with U.N. relevant
resolutions after Iraq reverses its policy of suspending its
cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who arrive here over the weekend at the invitation of the
U.N. chief, met with Annan Monday morning. He is due to meet with
the council's members during the course of the week. He is also
planning to meet the U.N. chief on the weekend. 
</P>
