several other members of the party have been detained by the
police because of the alleged links with the PKK which has been
fighting since 1984 for an independent state in southeastern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Perincek has reportedly begun a hunger strike to protest the
detention.
</P>
<P>
Reports have said the police uncovered three unlicensed guns in
IP's office building in the capital. But Perincek said that he
knew nothing about the guns.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of IP members from across the country staged a
demonstration Monday in Ankara to protest the detention of their
party leaders.
</P>
<P>
IP Deputy Chairman Hasan Yalcin read out a statement during the
demonstration, saying that "no one could ban us from politics."
</P>
