<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Rwandan Mayor Pleads Lenient Penalty for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 28 (Xinhua) -- A former Rwandan mayor
in connection with the 1994 genocide pleaded Monday with judges
of the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) to hand
down a less severe penalty on him.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations court, based in Arusha, north Tanzania,
will on October 2 sentence Jean-Paul Akayesu, former mayor of
Taba in central Rwanda, after finding him guilty of genocide and
crimes against humanity early this month.
</P>
<P>
According to a ICTR statement faxed to Xinhua, Akayesu said
during his pre-sentence hearing at the court that it was
difficult for him to prevent the killings because he was
powerless at that time.
</P>
<P>
"I was a mere bourgmestre (mayor) with only eight police
officers," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am asking for pardon... I regret what happened in Rwanda."
he said. "I also lost my relatives, my friends and many others,"
he told a panel of three judges -- the president of the court,
Laity Kama of Senegal, Lennart Aspegren of Sweden and Navanethem
Pillay of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"I cry for all these people and God please forgive me. I place
my fate in your hands. Honorable judges, and before God. I am
innocent in this case," he pleaded for mercy.
</P>
<P>
At least 500,000 people, primarily Tutsis and moderate Hutus,
were brutally massacred in just three months in the middle of
1994 in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council set up the ICTR in November of that
year to try chief suspects of the genocide. The maximum sentence
the court can impose is life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Prosecution Trial Attorney Pierre Prosper requested the
Chamber 1 of the court to impose a sentence which is retributive
and deterrent because of the gravity of the offence committed by
Akayesu.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor asked the chamber to impose multiple sentences
of life imprisonment on the accused for count one of genocide,
count three of crimes against humanity (extermination), count
four, direct and public incitement to commit genocide
(incitement), and count 13 of crimes against humanity (rape).
</P>
<P>
He also asked for multiple sentencing to life imprisonment of
a minimum of 30 years for counts five, seven and nine of crimes
against humanity (murder), a minimum of 25 years in prison for
count 11 of crimes against humanity (torture) and 10 years
imprisonment for count 14, crimes against humanity (inhumane
acts).
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor argued that, in determining the sentence, the
chamber should take into account the general practice in Rwanda
regarding prison sentences, the gravity of the offence, and the
individual circumstances of the convicted person, any
circumstances in aggravation and/or mitigation and consider other
sources in arriving at the sentence.
</P>
<P>
The United States ambassador to Tanzania, Rev. Charles Stith,
visited the tribunal and attended the pre-sentencing hearing in
the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980929.0323 </DOCNO>
