<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Troops to Stay in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Southern African troops
would remain in Lesotho until order is restored in the country,
the defense ministers of Zimbabwe, South Africa and Botswana said
in Maseru, capital of Lesotho, Monday.
</P>
<P>
The three countries are guarantors of peace in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The ministers maintained that the military intervention in
Lesotho last week by troops from South Africa and Botswana was in
line with Southern African Development Community (SADC)
agreements that no legitimate government in a member country
should be toppled by the military, said South African Press
Association (SAPA).
</P>
<P>
South African and Lesotho opposition parties have called for
the withdrawal of SADC troops as a first step toward talks to
resolve Lesotho's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The troops entered Lesotho last Tuesday in response to a
request by the Lesotho government, who said it feared an imminent
coup from mutinous soldiers and opposition parties. Claims by
Lesotho's political opposition that the country's general
elections in May were rigged to return the ruling party to power
triggered protests in the country.
</P>
<P>
The intervention sparked fierce fighting between rebel
soldiers and SADC troops, and arson and looting which destroyed
much of Maseru business center.
</P>
<P>
Although approximately 100 people are thought to have been
killed in the SADC intervention, confusion still surrounded the
official death toll Monday evening, said SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho police said Monday afternoon that 47 civilians were
killed and 15 injured in the fighting. Red Cross officials
claimed over the weekend that they had collected 68 bodies in
various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
By Monday evening, neither the Lesotho government nor the Red
Cross could confirm the official death toll and it was rumored
that families had already collected the remains of their loved
ones and buried them.
</P>
<P>
The SADC force said 58 Lesotho and eight South African
soldiers died in skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
South African Defense Minister Joe Modise Monday warned
remaining rebel Lesotho soldiers hiding in the mountains that
they would be hunted down and dealt with severely.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, efforts are being made to get the Lesotho
government and opposition parties to the negotiating table as the
South African government continued to justify the intervention in
the face of widespread criticism.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho King Letsie III is to meet South African President
Nelson Mandela in Cape Town Tuesday. Mandela requested the
meeting to share ideas with the king about developments in the
kingdom, and particularly to give fresh impetus to normalizing
the situation, and to political negotiations for a lasting
solution.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition parties indicated that they were willing to
negotiate with the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
