<HEADLINE> International Financial Market Urged to Be Reformed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and the
Philippines, hit by the Asian financial crisis, called Monday for
the reform of the international financial market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the annual U.N. General Assembly debate, Malaysian
Foreign Minister Abdullah Badawi said, "significant changes should
be made to the international financial architecture."
</P>
<P>
Complaining that the international financial markets lack
transparency, he called for rules governing the currency
transactions.
</P>
<P>
"In today's financial system, more than 1.2 trillion U.S.
dollars of currency is bought and sold every 24 hours," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no system of surveillance, no open reporting of any
kind and no WTO (World Trade Organization) kind of regulating
authority for this most lucrative trade in the coveted commodity,
that is money itself," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said developing countries should be given the time to
strengthen their economies, enabling them to participate
meaningfully in global free trade.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Minister Domingo Siazon told the General
Assembly that the Bretton Woods institutions, particularly the
International Monetary Fund, are insufficient in containing the
Asian financial crisis and restoring the health of affected
economies.
</P>
<P>
Industrialized countries should contribute to the replenishment
of IMF resources, to lend support for increasing the funds of the
World Bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Asian financial crisis as his country's
immediate global concern, the minister urged rich nations to
remove export barriers for goods from the developing countries and
give more development aid to bring South Asian economies back to
normal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
